1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 e6 3. e3 c5 4. c3 $5 h6 5. Bh4 cxd4 6. exd4 Be7 7. Nf3 b6 8.
Bd3 Bb7 9. O-O O-O 10. Nbd2 d6 {With ...d6 followed by ...Nbd7 Black goes for
a Hedgehog setup. This can be played against various openings.} (10... Ba6 11.
Bxa6 Nxa6 12. Qe2 Nc7 13. Ne5) ({An example of what NOT to do:} 10... Nc6 {
In the Hedgehog setup this knight belongs to d7.} 11. Re1 ({Even if White
would have developed his bishop to c4} 11. Bc4 d5 $2 {would still be bad. The
extra tempo is irrelevant here.} 12. Bd3 $16) ({Only once White plays} 11. c4
d5 $1 {becomes a good move! Now our b7-bishop will soon have an open diagonal
again (either White takes on d5, when we recapture with our knight, or we will
play ...dxc4), while ...d6-d5 fixes White's - now isolated - pawn on d4.} {
After for example} 12. a3 dxc4 13. Nxc4 {Black has a very good version of an
IQP position. If in such a position Black can develop his light-squared bishop
to an active diagonal so easily, something went wrong for White. Also: White's
queen's knight belongs to c3 (from where it controls the important d5-square)
rather than c4.} Nh5 $1 (13... Nd5 14. Bg3 $1 $11) 14. Bxe7 Nxe7 15. Nfe5 Nf4
$17) 11... d5 $2 {This is a big strategical mistake. Now the b7-bishop is
permanently blocked and White has a free hand on the kingside. He can start an
attack with, for instance} 12. Ne5) 11. Qe2 {Black's pawn does not belong on
h6 but on h7 in these positions. Apart from that, he has played a great game!
Anyway, after White's 12.Ne4?! the drawback of having the pawn on h6 pawn
cannot be seen.} Nbd7 {There is no clear way for White to make progress. His
best policy lies in quiet manoeuvering, waiting for an inaccuracy by Black.}
12. Ne4 $6 {Many players go for this impatient move. Exchanging pieces only
helps Black - he will be able to execute a minority attack. By studying this
game we will learn how to play such positions till deeply in the endgame.} (12.
Rfe1 Re8 13. h3 a6 14. Bg3 (14. Nf1 Qc7 15. a4 Qc8 16. c4 d5) 14... Qc7) 12...
Bxe4 {A small psychological trick. White may think, that after} 13. Bxe4 {
we might not take his bishop and he will be left with the pair of bishops.}
Nxe4 {But we take it of course...} 14. Qxe4 ({We have also set White a small
trap:} 14. Bxe7 $2 {loses a pawn due to} Nxc3 $1 15. bxc3 Qxe7 $17) 14... d5 {
Now ...d5 is perfectly good since we already exchanged our b7-bishop. However,
Black had also other possibilities, like for example} ({I would like to avoid} 
14... Nf6 15. Bxf6) (14... Bxh4 {may be even best objectively.} 15. Nxh4 b5 16.
Nf3 Qb6 17. Qe2 d5 {[%cal Yb5b4] Before we play ...b4, the move ...d5 is
obligatory.} ({The immediate} 17... b4 $2 {is a strategical mistake because of
the reply} 18. c4)) 15. Qg4 Bxh4 16. Qxh4 Qxh4 17. Nxh4 b5 $1 $15 {The
minority attack is a matter of tempi! If White could swing over his knight to
d3, then he would be fine, but here Black is better.} 18. Nf3 (18. a4 Rfb8 ({
Black can also consider} 18... a6 {with the idea to prepare ...b4 with ...Rfb8
or to play ...Nb6, forcing the a-pawn to declare his intentions.}) 19. axb5
Rxb5 20. b4 Nf6 $1 $17 {[%csl Rc3,Ge4][%cal Yf6e4]}) 18... Rab8 19. a3 a5 {
Preparing ...b4.} 20. Rfe1 (20. Ne5 $2 Nxe5 21. dxe5 {This structure is even
better for Black than the one with the pawn on d4. For example} Rfc8 22. Rfe1
Rc4 {Now the c4-rook has influence on the half-open c-file AND the 4th rank.}
23. g3 b4 $17 (23... g5 $5 $17)) 20... Rfc8 21. Ne5 $6 Nxe5 22. Rxe5 b4 $17 23.
axb4 ({Taking with the c-pawn} 23. cxb4 $6 axb4 {and playing} 24. a4 {is
rarely a good option for White.} Rc4 $17 (24... b3 $17) (24... Rc2 $17)) (23.
Re3 $2 {is clearly worse compared to 23.axb4 axb4 24.Re3, since the presence
of the a-pawns is in Black's favor.} bxc3 24. bxc3 Rb3 {Here White has two
weaknesses - c3 and a3.} 25. Rc1 Rxa3 $19) 23... axb4 24. Re3 bxc3 25. bxc3 ({
How to continue after} 25. Rxc3 {?} Rf8 $3 {If Black is able to find this
great move (or 25...Re8!! or 25...Rd8!!), White is suddenly left with 2
weaknesses to protect - d4 and b2 -, rather than just one on c3. A possible
continuation:} 26. b3 Rb4 27. Rd3 Rfb8 28. Ra3 g5 $1 {We have two ways to
develop the king; centralize it, or as in this case, preparing to put it on g6.
...g5 is an important move: we gain space and at the same time prepare to
activate the king. In the next phase Black will try to create another weakness.
} (28... h5 {is the wrong idea.} 29. h4 g6 30. g3 Kg7 {Here our king is stuck
on g7 and it's difficult to achieve something. For example} 31. Kg2 f6 32. f4
Kh6 33. Kf2 g5 34. fxg5+ fxg5 35. hxg5+ Kxg5 $11) 29. h3 Kg7 30. Kf1 Kg6 31.
Ke2 h5 $17 {etc.}) 25... Rb2 {How should White defend? 26.Rc1 or 26.g3?} 26. g3
{White finds the right idea.} (26. Rc1 $2 {loses a pawn after} Rd2 $1 (26...
Rb4 27. Rd3) 27. Rb1 Rc2 $19 {as White cannot defend the pawn with} 28. Rb3 $4
{due to} Rc1+) 26... Rc2 27. Ra3 g5 $3 {Typical and strong! We win space, fix
White's h- and f-pawn, and prepare a path for our king to move forward.} ({
After} 27... h5 28. h4 {our possibilities are limited. For example} g6 29. Kg2
Kg7 (29... Rb8 30. Ra7 Rbb2 31. Rf3) 30. Kf1 f6 31. f4 Kf7 32. Re2 Rc1+ 33. Kf2
Rc2 34. Kf3 Rc1 35. Re3 $11) 28. h3 (28. f4 $2 {weakens the second rank.} Rb8
$19) 28... Kg7 29. g4 (29. Kg2 Kg6 30. Kg1 h5 31. Kg2 g4 32. hxg4 hxg4 $17 {
Fixing the f2-pawn and controlling f3 - Black's position is technically
winning.}) 29... Rc7 30. Kg2 Kg6 31. Rb3 h5 $3 32. Ra3 h4 $3 {The h4 pawn
spells real trouble for White! If in some scenario we win the h3-pawn, our
h-pawn can become very powerful.} 33. Rf3 Rc1 34. Ra8 Kg7 35. Ra3 Rb7 $3 {
Another great move which helps to show the strength of the h4-pawn. After a
possible ...Rbb1, mating threats arise.} 36. Re3 Rbb1 37. Ra7 Kg6 $1 {Before
executing the decisive manoeuvre Black defends against Rxe6.} 38. Ra8 Rh1 $3
$19 {White no longer has a satisfactory defence.} 39. Rg8+ Kf6 40. f4 {A
desperate move, though after continuations Black wins the h3-pawn.} (40. Rf3+
Ke7 41. Re3 Rbg1+ 42. Kf3 Rxh3+ 43. Ke2 Rxe3+ 44. fxe3 Rxg4 $19) (40. Rc8 Rbg1+
41. Kf3 Rxh3+ 42. Ke2 Rxe3+ $19) 40... Rbg1+ 41. Kf2 Rf1+ 42. Kg2 gxf4 43. g5+
Ke7 44. Rd3 Rhg1+ 45. Kh2 Rg3 {A great game by Black, played at the same level
as a good GM!!} 0-1

