{Another great game, demonstrating the typical ideas of the minority attack,
again coming from the Hedgehog setup against the Torre Attack.} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 c5 4. e3 cxd4 5. exd4 Be7 6. Bd3 b6 7. O-O Bb7 8. c3 d6 9. Nbd2
Nbd7 10. Qe2 a6 11. Ne4 $6 {White typically loses his patience! After this the
position is still about equal, but Black has the easier play.} O-O 12. Nxf6+
Nxf6 ({We can consider} 12... Bxf6 {when I guess that White keeps the bishop
on the board with} 13. Bd2) 13. Rfe1 (13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Be4 Bxe4 15. Qxe4 d5
16. Qe2 b5 17. Ne5 Bxe5 18. dxe5 Qb6 19. Rad1 Rac8 20. Rfe1 Rc4) ({We already
know what to play after} 13. c4 d5 $1 14. cxd5 Nxd5 $15 ({Let's discuss an
idea after} 14... Bxd5 {Now, for the purpose to illustrate my point, I insert}
15. Rfd1 {and} Re8 {Does Black get enough compensation after} 16. Bxa6 Bxf3 17.
gxf3 Nd5 18. Be3 Bd6 $17 {The answer is yes - this is very good Black.})) (13.
a4 {will be dealt with in the theory session.}) 13... Re8 {Black has a great
game.} 14. Rad1 Qc7 {White has no direct plan, while Black always has the idea
of a minority attack.} (14... b5 15. Ra1 Bc6) 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Be4 b5 $1 (
16... d5 $4 {is the positional mistake to avoid!!} 17. Bb1 $16 b5 18. Ne5 Rab8
19. Rd3 {White has a clear attacking plan.} Bxe5 20. dxe5 {White must keep the
queens on the board - he needs his queen to execute his attack.} (20. Qxe5 $4
Qxe5 21. Rxe5 a5 $15 {is already better for Black since he can prepare a
minority attack.}) 20... Bc6 21. Rh3 g6 22. Qe3 $18) ({First exchanging bishops
} 16... Bxe4 17. Qxe4 {and only afterwards playing} d5 {is however possible.})
17. Bxb7 Qxb7 18. Qe4 $2 (18. h3 Rac8 (18... b4 $2 {is premature as White can
play} 19. c4 {and after} d5 20. c5) 19. Qe3 {If White loses control over the
c4-square, then} b4 {is strong.} 20. cxb4 Qxb4 21. b3 a5 {and Black continues
with ...a4 - a mini minority attack.}) 18... Qxe4 19. Rxe4 d5 $1 $17 {with a
clear advantage for Black in the endgame due to the possibility for a minority
attack. I personally prefer to play for a minority attack in the endgame since
without queens White cannot start a counterattack on the kingside.} 20. Re3 a5
21. Ne5 (21. Ne1 {with the idea to put the knight on d3 is too slow. It works,
however, if Black went to sleep:} h6 22. Nd3 Rad8 23. a3 Be7 24. b4 {Given
time, White can create an outpost on c5 for his knight.} Rc8 25. Nc5 Ra8 {
Even here Black cannot complain.}) 21... Bxe5 $1 22. dxe5 $6 (22. Rxe5 $15)
22... Rec8 23. Rd4 Rc4 $5 24. Rxc4 bxc4 {With more pieces on the board, this
position could be good for White. For example with a bishop on c1 and queens
on the board, White could solidly defend b2 and organize an attack on the
kingside. As it is, Black is clearly better.} 25. Kf1 Rb8 (25... a4 26. a3 Rb8)
26. Re2 a4 27. Rd2 g5 $3 $19 {The typical endgame move! Gaining space,
isolating e5, and preparing to activate our king! We also have other candidate
moves:} (27... f6 $1 28. exf6 gxf6 $17) (27... Kf8 28. a3 {Now, please do not
play a move like} Rb3 $2 {The rook has nothing to do on b3.} (28... g5 $1) (
28... f6 $1)) 28. Ke2 Kg7 29. a3 Kg6 {A clever move. Black wants to provoke g4,
and then play ...f6.} (29... f6 30. exf6+ Kxf6 {with the idea to prepare ...
e5-d4 is another strong idea.}) 30. Ke3 (30. g4 f6 31. exf6 Kxf6 {Compared to
29...f6, the situation is worse for White, since g2-g4 has created some
weaknesses. For example} 32. f3 (32. Ke3 Ke5) 32... Rb5 {with the idea ...e5.}
({or} 32... h5 33. h3 h4 (33... Rh8)) 33. Ke3 e5 34. Ke2 (34. Re2 Ke6 {If
White tries} 35. h4 {we should not be scared and enter the complications. For
example} gxh4 36. Rh2 Rb3 37. Rxh4 Rxb2 38. Rh6+ Kf7 39. Rxh7+ Kf6) 34... Ke6
35. Ke3 Kd6 36. Ke2 Kc5 37. Ke3 Rb3 $19 {[%cal Yd5d4] Now the rook makes sense
on b3 since we are threatening ...d4+.}) 30... f6 (30... Kf5 $5 31. Kd4 f6) 31.
f4 Kf5 $1 32. exf6 gxf4+ 33. Kf3 Rd8 (33... Rf8 $1 $19) 34. f7 Rf8 35. Rd4 Rxf7
36. Rxf4+ Kg6 $19 {The pawn ending is winning for Black.} 37. Rxf7 Kxf7 38. g4
e5 39. h4 Kf6 40. Ke3 Ke6 41. Kf3 d4 42. cxd4 exd4 43. Ke4 d3 44. Ke3 Ke5 45.
h5 Kf6 0-1

