1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 h6 4. Bh4 c5 5. e3 cxd4 6. exd4 Be7 7. Bd3 b6 8. Bg3
{Now we have some kind of London System. Imagine that White has played Bf4-g3.}
Ba6 $1 {This is another nice idea to remember! Quite often - instead of ...Bb7
- it is equally good to play ...Ba6!.} 9. Bxa6 Nxa6 10. O-O O-O 11. Nbd2 b5 12.
a3 Nc7 13. c3 Ncd5 14. Re1 Qb6 {Black's plan consists of preparing ...a5 and ..
.b4. The latter move will be played if the reply c3-c4 is no longer possible.}
15. Ne5 Rfc8 $15 16. Bh4 d6 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Nd3 a5 19. Ne4 Be7 20. Rc1 Qa6 ({
For the moment we cannot play} 20... b4 {due to} 21. axb4 axb4 22. c4) 21. Qf3
Rab8 22. g3 b4 $1 $15 {Finally ...b4 happens - after Black has taken c4 under
control.} 23. axb4 axb4 24. cxb4 Nxb4 25. Rxc8+ Qxc8 $17 {White has weaknesses
on d4 and b2.} 26. Rc1 Qd7 27. Nxb4 Rxb4 28. d5 e5 {Now we have a structure
resembling the Najdorf. Black has a majority on the kingside and is about to
push ...f5-e4.} 29. Qe2 f5 30. Nc3 e4 31. Ra1 Bf6 32. h4 Kh7 $19 {Black's king
is very safe on h7. Before starting some action, he improved his king position.
} 33. h5 Qb7 34. Nd1 Qxd5 35. Ne3 Qc5 36. Ra2 Bd4 37. Nd1 Rb3 38. Kg2 Rd3 39.
Ra3 Rxa3 40. bxa3 Qxa3 41. Ne3 Bxe3 42. fxe3 Qc5 43. Qf2 Qd5 44. Qf4 Qe5 45.
Qh4 Qb2+ 46. Kh3 Qc1 {A high-level game!} 0-1

