{Another excellent game with the typical plans of the minority attack carried
out in the endgame!} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bg4 6.
O-O e6 7. c3 Bd6 8. Qa4+ Nbd7 9. Ne5 O-O 10. Nxg4 (10. Nxd7 {Here are some
sample lines of a minority attack with an early exchange of queens - Black is
already better!} Qxd7 11. Qxd7 (11. Qc2 Bh5 (11... b5) (11... Bf5)) 11... Nxd7
12. Be3 Bh5 13. Nd2 Bg6 14. Bxg6 hxg6 15. Nf3 b5 16. g3 (16. a4 b4) (16. h4 Nb6
) 16... Rfc8 17. Nd2 a5 (17... b4 18. cxb4 Bxb4 19. b3 Ba3 20. Nf3 f6 21. Rfe1
Kf7 22. Nd2 g5 (22... a5 23. h4)) 18. a3 f6 (18... a4) 19. Rfd1 (19. h4) 19...
g5 20. Kf1 g4 21. Ke2 Kf7 (21... a4 22. Rac1 Nb6 $17) 22. Rdc1 Rab8 (22... a4
23. Rc2 Rh8 24. Nf1 Nb6 25. Rd1 Nc4 26. Bc1 Rad8 27. Ke1 Bc7 28. Ke2 e5 29.
dxe5 fxe5 30. Be3 Ke6 $19) 23. b4 a4 $17) 10... Nxg4 11. h3 Ngf6 {We started
from a completely different opening, but have arrived at the same pawn
structure as in our previous examples. In the Torre we can get a position like
this by first exchanging our light-squared bishop and then play ...d6-d5.} 12.
Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 Qc7 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 15. Nd2 a6 (15... e5 16. dxe5 Bxe5 17. Nf3) (
15... Qd7 16. Qd1 b5 17. b4) (15... Nh5) 16. Qd1 b5 {Black starts his minority
attack on the queenside, while White has no counterplay on the kingside.} 17.
a3 (17. a4 b4 (17... Qb6 18. axb5 axb5 19. b4 $15)) (17. Re1 b4 18. Rc1 (18.
cxb4 Bxb4 19. Rf1 Bxd2 20. Qxd2 Qb6 21. Bc2 (21. Be2 Rfb8 22. b3 a5 23. Rac1 a4
24. bxa4 Rxa4 $19 {[%csl Ra2,Rd4]}) 21... Rab8 22. b3 a5 $15) (18. c4 dxc4 19.
Nxc4 $15) 18... bxc3 19. bxc3 $15 (19. Rxc3 Qb6 $17)) (17. Ne4 Be7 18. Nxf6+
Bxf6 19. Qe2 Qb6 20. Rad1 b4 21. cxb4 Qxb4 22. Bxa6 Qa4 23. Bd3 Qxa2 $17 {
[%csl Rb2,Rd4]}) 17... Rab8 (17... Qb6 18. b4 Rfc8 19. Rc1 e5 (19... Rab8 $2
20. Re1 Rc7 21. Nb3 Rbc8 22. Nc5) 20. dxe5 (20. Nb3 e4 21. Be2 Re8 (21... Bc7))
20... Bxe5 21. Nb3 Rxc3 (21... Rc7 22. Nc5 Bd6 23. Nb3 Rac8)) 18. Qe2 Rfe8 19.
Rfe1 Re7 20. Nf3 Nh5 $1 {I really like this move!} 21. Ne5 $6 (21. g3 Bxg3 22.
fxg3 Qxg3+ 23. Qg2 Qxg2+ 24. Kxg2 Nf4+) 21... Nf4 22. Qf3 {How should Black
continue?} Nxd3 (22... Bxe5 $1 $15 {Exchanging everything would have been
best! Here are some sample lines, skillfully demonstrating the motifs in the
endgame.} 23. Rxe5 (23. dxe5 $6 {We already know that with a white pawn on e5,
Black has an even better version of the minority attack.} Nxd3 24. Qxd3 Qc8 25.
Re2 Rc7 26. Rd1 Rc4 {[%csl Gc4]} 27. g3 a5 $17) 23... Nxd3 24. Qxd3 {Let's see
how the game can develop from here. Knowing how to play such positions will
raise your understanding of strategy and endgame play!} a5 25. Re3 b4 (25...
Qc4 26. Qxc4 $2 bxc4 $17 {[%csl Rb2]} 27. Re2 Reb7 28. Ra2 (28. Rb1 $2 Rb3 $1
29. Rc2 Rxa3 $19) 28... g5 $1 {[%cal Yg8g7,Yg7g6,Yh6h5]} 29. g3 Kg7 30. f4 (30.
Kg2 Kg6 31. g4 h5 32. f3 Rb6 33. Kf2 f6 34. Kg2 a4 35. Kf2 Re8 36. Kg2 e5 $17)
30... gxf4 (30... Kg6 31. Kf2) 31. gxf4 Kg6 32. Kf2 Rb6 $17 (32... f6 33. Kf3
Kf5 $17) 33. Kf3 f6 34. Rg2+ Kf5 35. Rg7 Rb5 36. Rh7 R5b6 37. Rxh6 Rb5 38. h4
Rxb2 $19) 26. cxb4 axb4 27. axb4 (27. a4 b3 $15 {[%csl Rd4]}) 27... Rxb4 28.
Ra8+ Rb8 29. Rxb8+ Qxb8 {[%csl Rb2,Rd4]} 30. Qd2 $2 Rb7 $1 31. b3 Rxb3 32. Rxb3
Qxb3 $19) 23. Qxd3 (23. Nxd3 $1 $11 {The knight is well placed on d3 in this
structure.} a5 (23... Qb6 24. b4) 24. Rac1 Qa7 25. b4) 23... a5 24. Rac1 Bxe5
25. Rxe5 ({Again we would be happy to see} 25. dxe5 $6 {For example} Qc8 (25...
Qc4 26. Qxc4 bxc4 $17 27. Rc2 Reb7 28. Ree2 g5 29. g3 Kg7 30. Kf1 f6 31. exf6+
Kxf6 32. Kg2 e5 $17) 26. Re2 Rc7 27. g3 (27. f4 b4 28. axb4 axb4 29. f5 exf5
30. Qxd5 Rc5 $15 (30... bxc3 31. bxc3 Rxc3 32. Rxc3 Qxc3 33. e6 $132)) 27...
Rc4 $17) 25... Qd6 26. Re3 Rc7 27. Rg3 Qf4 28. Re1 b4 29. axb4 (29. cxb4 axb4
30. a4 b3 {[%csl Rd4]}) 29... axb4 30. Rg4 (30. cxb4 Rxb4 $17 {[%csl Rb2,Rd4]}
31. Rg4 Qf6 32. b3 Rcb7 33. Re3 h5 34. Rgg3 Qxd4 35. Qxd4 Rxd4) 30... Qd6 31.
Qd2 Kh7 32. Rg3 bxc3 33. bxc3 (33. Rxc3 Rcb7 $1 {[%csl Rb2,Rd4]} (33... Rxc3
34. bxc3 Kg8 35. g3 Qc6 36. Re3 Qa4 $15) 34. Qc2+ g6 (34... Kg8 $4 35. Rc8+ $18
) 35. b3 Kg7 36. Rd1 Rb4 37. g3 Qb6 38. Rd2 Rxb3 39. Rxb3 Qxb3 40. Qxb3 Rxb3
$19 {Let's see how Black can win such a position:} 41. Kg2 (41. h4 Kf6 42. Kg2
(42. g4 Rh3 $19) 42... Kf5 $19 {[%cal Yf5e4]}) 41... g5 42. Kh2 Kg6 43. g4 h5
44. Kg2 h4 45. Kh2 f6 46. Kg2 Kf7 47. Kh2 Ke7 48. Kg2 Kd6 49. Kh2 e5 50. dxe5+
fxe5 51. Ra2 d4 52. Ra6+ Kd5 53. Rg6 d3 54. Rxg5 Ke4 (54... d2 55. Rg8 Rd3 56.
Rd8+ Ke4 57. f3+ Ke3) (54... Kd4 55. Rg8 Kc3 56. Rc8+ Kb2 57. Rd8 Kc2 58. Kg2
d2 59. g5 d1=Q 60. Rxd1 Kxd1 61. g6) 55. Rg8 d2) 33... Rcb7 34. Qe3 g6 35. Qe5
Qxe5 36. dxe5 Rb1 37. Rge3 Kg7 38. g3 R1b3 39. Rd3 Rc8 40. Ree3 Rc7 41. Kg2 g5
$1 {The right idea!} ({Black's possibilities are limited after} 41... h5 42. h4
{. He is still better, but it's difficult to make progress.} Rc4 43. f4 f6 44.
exf6+ Kxf6 45. Kf3) 42. g4 (42. f4 gxf4 43. gxf4 Kg6 44. Kf3 Kf5 45. Kg3 Rc4
46. Rf3 Re4 47. Rde3 Rxe3 48. Rxe3 d4 49. Re1 Rxc3+ 50. Kh4 Kxf4 51. Rf1+ Rf3
$19) (42. Kh2 Rc4 43. Kg2 f6 44. exf6+ Kxf6 45. Kh2 e5 (45... e5) (45... Rb5)
