1. Nf3 Nf6 2. d4 e6 3. e3 {The Colle System - the good thing for White about
this opening is flexibility.} c5 (3... b6 {is playable as well. White has
several setups:} 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. b3 ({or} 5. c4 {followed by Nc3.}) 5... d5 6.
Bb2 Nbd7 7. O-O Be7 8. Nbd2) 4. Bd3 (4. c4 cxd4 5. exd4 d5 6. Nc3 Bb4 {can
lead to a Nimzo Indian.}) 4... cxd4 5. exd4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 b6 8. c4 Bb7
9. b3 d5 {Black has a solid setup and will take at some point on c4. For
instance if White is threatening to play c4-c5.} 10. Bb2 Nc6 (10... dxc4 {
is playable but a little less flexible.} 11. bxc4 {Is it better to develop our
knight to c6 or d7?} {If we have the chance we develop the knight to} Nc6 $1 {
From here the knight puts pressure on d4 and can later attack the c4-pawn with
...Na5.} ({After} 11... Nbd7 12. Nbd2 Rc8 13. Qe2 {we have a stable but
somewhat passive position. The knight on d7 cannot go anywhere!})) ({Let's see
an idea for White if Black plays random moves like} 10... Re8 11. Nbd2 a6 12.
Rc1 Bf8 13. a3 h6 {Now} 14. c5 $1 {would be very strong, leading to a huge
advantage.} bxc5 15. dxc5 Nc6 16. b4 $18) 11. Nbd2 Nb4 $1 {This is a nice
idea! We play ...Nb4 before White has played Rc1 (when the bishop could
comfortably drop back to b1). We aim to provoke the move a2-a3 which is to his
advantage!} ({If we play} 11... Rc8 12. Rc1 dxc4 13. bxc4 Na5 {with the pawn
still on a2, then White has the annoying move} 14. Nb3 $1) 12. Bf1 Rc8 13. a3 (
{Let's play random moves for White to see Black's idea:} 13. h3 Re8 {Black
prepares ...Bf8, ...g6, ...Bg7.} 14. Bc3 Bf8 15. a3 Nc6 16. Bd3 g6 17. Bb2 dxc4
18. bxc4 Bg7 {The hanging pawns provide with some attacking chances. However,
if we manage to put the bishop on g7, White remains with zero attacking
chances!}) 13... Nc6 14. Rc1 dxc4 $1 {Don't forget to play ...dc4! when you
feel that White is threatening c4-c5!} (14... Re8 15. c5 $1) 15. bxc4 Re8 16.
Bd3 Bf8 $1 17. Ne4 (17. Nf1 g6 {If we manage to play ...Bg7, we are completely
safe, so it's important to check whether White can play d4-d5:} 18. d5 (18. Ng3
Bg7 19. h3 Na5 $1 $15 (19... Rc7 $6 20. Qe2 Qa8 $6 {Please do not play such
plans - they are almost always bad. In the coming complications the queen
might turn out to be too far away from the action.}) (19... Re7 $5 $15 {
[%cal Ye7d7,Yd7c7]})) 18... exd5 19. Rxe8 Nxe8 20. cxd5 Qxd5 {I don't see
anything good for White - d4-d5 does not work.}) 17... Nxe4 18. Bxe4 Na5 $1 19.
Bxb7 (19. Bd3 g6 20. d5 (20. Bc3 Bxa3 21. Ra1 Bf8 $17) (20. h3 $2 Bxf3 21. Qxf3
Bg7 22. Red1 Nc6 $17 (22... Nb3 $2 23. Bxg6)) 20... Bg7 21. Bxg7 Kxg7 22. dxe6
Rxe6 23. Rxe6 fxe6 24. Qe2 Qf6 25. Be4 Bxe4 26. Qxe4 Rxc4 $1 27. Rxc4 Qa1+ 28.
Ne1 Nxc4 $11) 19... Nxb7 $15 {Many pieces have been exchanged which favors the
side playing against the hanging pawns. The position is objectively still
about equal but Black is slightly better in a practical sense!} 20. g3 Na5 21.
Qd3 {Now I played a very deep move:} f6 $1 {This move could be a bad mistake
but in this position it appears to be very powerful! I stop Ng5 and Ne5 and
prepare ...e5 or the manoeuvre ...Qd7-a4. The weakening of the e6-pawn cannot
be exploited. In the further course, I played ...e5 at a good moment - you
will study the rest of the game by yourself.} ({I prefer to avoid} 21... Qd7
22. Ng5 g6 {White was able to provoke some weaknesses and now gets a strong
initiative with} 23. d5 $1 $16) 22. Nd2 Qd7 23. Re3 e5 24. dxe5 Qxd3 25. Rxd3
fxe5 26. Re1 Red8 27. Rxd8 Rxd8 28. Re2 Rd3 29. Kg2 e4 $1 30. a4 e3 $1 31. fxe3
Bb4 32. Nf1 Nxc4 33. Bd4 a6 34. g4 b5 35. axb5 axb5 36. Kf3 Rd1 37. Ng3 Nd2+
$15 38. Kf4 $6 Bd6+ 39. Be5 $2 Bxe5+ 40. Kxe5 b4 41. Kd4 (41. Nf5 b3 42. g5 b2
43. Rf2 Kf7 44. Nd6+ Kg6 $19 (44... Ke7 $4 45. Rf7+ Kd8 46. Ke6 b1=Q 47. Rd7#))
41... b3 42. Kc3 Rc1+ 43. Kxd2 b2 0-1

