1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {With this move order, White avoids for example the
Bogo-Indian, so we must find something else.} b5 {In my opinion this is the
best move in this position in a practical and maybe also in a theoretical
sense. I played this position several times with the white and the black
pieces. In all of the games, Black was better shortly after the opening. White
needs to be a real expert to put Black under some pressure. With 3...b5 we
control c4 and quickly solve the problem of neutralising White's Catalan
bishop by developing our bishop to b7.} ({The main move is} 3... d5 {,
entering a Catalan. No thanks!}) {For example} 4. Bg2 (4. Qd3 {was shown to me
by GM Atalik. White attacks b5 and threatens e2-e4. However we can play} a6 ({
or the artistic} 4... Ba6 $5) 5. e4 Bb7 6. Nbd2 c5 {and our pieces are very
well placed for a counterattack against White's center.}) 4... Bb7 5. O-O c5 ({
We can even play} 5... d5 {This is no longer a regular Catalan, since White
cannot play c4.} {After for example} 6. Nbd2 c5 7. c3 Nbd7 {Black has already
gained some space on the queenside. Black isn't suffering from a bad bishop on
b7, since it can always be activated after a later ...a5, ...b4, via a6.}) 6.
c3 Na6 $5 *

