1. d4 Nf6 ({Let's compare our line with} 1... f5 2. Bg5 Nf6 $2 3. Bxf6 exf6 4.
e3 d5 {Surprisingly, this is a (very) bad version of the Trompowsky! With the
Black pawn on f6 instead of f7, White is much better!} 5. Nd2 $16 Nd7 6. c4
dxc4 7. Bxc4) 2. Bg5 {This is the Trompowsky Opening, named after Brazilian
player Octavio Trompowsky. By the early development White's dark-squared
bishop, the game gets an original positional character.} d5 $1 {This is the
best move for Black - the following play is based on natural moves. ONCE AGAIN
WE DO NOT NEED TO MEMORIZE CONCRETE THEORY, BUT ONLY NEED TO KNOW WHERE TO
DEVELOP OUR PIECES AND THE PLANS AFTER THAT!} (2... e6 {is another reliable
move. However it has the practical disadvantage to give White many different
options:} 3. e4 (3. Nd2) (3. e3) 3... h6 4. Bxf6 Qxf6 5. c3) (2... Ne4 {
was the main move, but I didn't like it right from the start. White has three
options:} 3. Bf4 {is the main move. Play can get quite sharp and White tends
to get good positions after this.} (3. h4 {is a favourite of GM Igor
Miladinovic.}) (3. Bh4 {is for coffee house chess.})) 3. Bxf6 {THIS is what
most Trompowsky players will go for with White.} (3. Nc3 {transposes to the
Veresov Opening.}) (3. e3 {is the other main option apart from 3.Bxf6.}) 3...
exf6 {I prefer this capture - it is much more solid than 3...gxf6.} 4. e3 {
Now, our next moves are going to be ...Bd6-c6-Nd7-f5!-Nf6-0-0-Qe7!-Bd7! etc.
in some move order. Of course, we keep your eyes open about what White does as
well! As a rule, we get solid reliable positions with good chances for
counterplay in the middlegame.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "TROMPOWSKY"]
[Black "THEORETICAL OVERVIEW"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D00"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "34"]
[EventDate "2024.06.10"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 d5 $1 3. Bxf6 {THIS is what most Trompowsky players will go
for with White.} (3. Nc3 {transposes to the Veresov Opening.}) (3. e3 $5 {
A playable alternative which nevertheless does not cause any problems! We play
3...c6!, giving White one last chance to transpose to the ...Bxf6-ef6
structures. If he does not accept, we continue with ...Bg4! and then ...Nbd7
followed by e6 or e5!} c6 $1 (3... c5 4. Bxf6 gxf6 {leads to a different
theoretical line.}) 4. Bd3 {Alternatives on the 4th are quite harmless:} (4.
Nd2 Bf5 $132 (4... Bg4 $132)) (4. c4 $6 {leads to some problems:} Ne4 5. Bf4 $2
(5. Bh4 Qb6 $36 (5... g5 6. Bg3 h5 $36)) 5... e5 $17 6. Bxe5 Bb4+ 7. Ke2 Nd7
$17 (7... Qh4 $17)) (4. Bxf6 exf6 {transposes to 3.Bxf6 exf6.}) 4... Bg4 $1 5.
Ne2 Nbd7 6. f3 (6. Nd2 e5 $36) 6... Bh5 7. Nbc3 (7. Nf4 $6 Bg6 8. Nxg6 hxg6 {
Black has a great game, because White has created a lot of weaknesses by
playing f3.} 9. Nd2 e5 $132) 7... e5 $1 $132 {Study the MODEL GAME 0-1 (94)
Grischuk,A (2794)-Dominguez Perez,L (2729) Tsaghkadzor 2015, and the games
17-26 in the database to learn the typical motifs in the line 3.e3.}) 3... exf6
{I prefer this capture - it is much more solid than 3...gxf6.} 4. e3 {Now, our
next moves are going to be ...Bd6-c6-Nd7-f5!-Nf6-0-0-Qe7!-Bd7! etc. in some
move order. Of course, we keep your eyes open about what White does as well!}
Bd6 {The alternatives are of equal value:} (4... c6) (4... Nd7) 5. c4 (5. g3 $5
{This is very common, but it doesn't change much. Our plans are very similar
to the other continuations!} c6 6. Bg2 Nd7 7. Ne2 f5 {Study the MODEL GAME 0-1
(77) Andreikin,D (2696)-Tomashevsky,E (2707) Khanty-Mansiysk 2011 and the
games number 8-12 in the database to see how to play against 5.g3!}) (5. Nd2 {
Again, we needn't change our plans after this.} f5 6. Bd3 {Now we have to be
careful! White can possibly transpose to the Mamedyarov plan - see 5.Bd3 for
the subtleties.} (6. Ngf3 Nd7 7. Be2 Nf6 $1 8. O-O c6 $132) 6... c6 7. Ne2 g6 {
Preparing ...Nd7 (we can also first play ...0-0).} (7... Be6 {We do not want
to put the bishop on e6, since it can be hit by Nf4 and we also don't want to
exchange it after} 8. c4 dxc4 9. Bxc4 $14) 8. O-O Nd7 9. c4 dxc4 10. Nxc4 Bc7
11. Qc2 Nf6 12. Rac1 O-O 13. g3 Qe7 {and we have reached our basic setup and
have a satisfactory game.}) (5. Bd3 {BE CAREFUL WHEN YOU SEE Bd3! - this
introduces the Mamedyarov plan. White plays Bd3-Qf3-Nd2-Ne2 and afterwards
wants to attack with the kingside pawns, e.g. g4-h4. We need to understand how
to stop this! We must be careful with our move order: when we see the move Bd3,
WE MUST MAKE SURE THAT WHTE IS NOT ABLE TO PLAY A FAST Qf3 followed by g4! To
prevent this, we need to postpone castling for a while!} c6 6. Nd2 Nd7 (6...
O-O $6 {After premature castling, White's plan works perfectly. See the MODEL
GAME 1-0 (18) Mamedyarov,S (2585)-Bagheri,A (2500) Abu Dhabi 2003, to
understand what we must avoid!}) 7. c3 (7. Qf3 g6 8. g4 h5 $1) 7... g6 $1 {
When we see Bd3, we postpone castling until White shows his hand!} (7... O-O $2
8. Qf3 g6 $2 9. g4 $1 $40 Nb6 10. Ne2 $16) 8. Qf3 $2 (8. Ngf3 $1 {White must
switch to positional play!} O-O 9. O-O f5 10. c4 Nf6 (10... dxc4) 11. cxd5 cxd5
$5 $15 (11... Nxd5 $36)) (8. g4 $2 h5) 8... f5 $1 $15 {check out the MODEL
GAME 0-1 (45) Mamedyarov,S (2764)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2778) Saint Louis 2019
and the games 14-16 from the database to understand how to successfully fight
against the Mamedyarov plan.} (8... O-O $2 9. g4 $1 $40)) 5... dxc4 $1 {
When we see an early c4, it's necessary to take!} (5... c6 $2 {is a strategic
mistake.} 6. cxd5 cxd5 $16 {Black has a very weak isolated pawn on d5, which
can be attacked by both of White's knights and his bishop. Also the position
is very static - which favours the knights over the pair of bishops.}) 6. Bxc4
{Now any move order is fine for Black. Please study the following analysis in
connection with the MODEL GAMES 4-7 in the database to get an understanding of
the possible plans for both sides.} Nd7 $1 (6... f5 $1 7. Ne2 (7. Nf3 Nd7 8.
Nbd2 O-O 9. O-O c6 10. Rb1 Qe7 11. a3 Nf6 12. Qc2 Bd7 13. Bd3 g6 14. Nc4 Bc7
15. b4 (15. Nce5 Be6 16. Bc4 Nd5) 15... Rac8 16. Rfc1 Be6 17. a4 Bd5 18. b5 (
18. Nfe5 Ng4 19. Nxg4 fxg4) 18... f4 19. Qe2 Rfe8 $17 {0-1 (80) Flaata,A (2096)
-Haug,J (2175)/Norway NOR 2015.}) 7... Nd7 8. O-O Nf6 9. Nbc3 c6 10. a4 $6 (10.
d5 c5 $1 $15 {is a good answer to d4-d5.} 11. Bb5+ (11. Nb5 O-O ({In this case
} 11... Bb8 {is also playable, with the idea} 12. d6 a6) 12. Nxd6 Qxd6 {
In general the queen is not a good blockading piece, but in this case it
cannot be attacked!}) 11... Kf8 $3 $17 {...g6-Kg7 fits well into our plans, so
we can keep the pair of bishops.} 12. Bd3 a6 13. a4 g6 (13... b6 {possibly can
be played.} 14. a5 $140 b5) 14. a5 Bd7 15. Qd2 (15. Na4 $2 Qxa5 $19) 15... Kg7
{Black is strategically much better, for example} (15... Bxh2+ $2 {fails after}
16. Kxh2 Ng4+ 17. Kh3 $1 $18 (17. Kg1 $2 Qh4 $19)) 16. Na4 Bxa4 17. Rxa4 Re8
18. Nc3 Qc7 19. g3 h5) 10... h5 {I played ...h5, maybe intending to sacrifice
on h2. Of course ...0-0 was also possible.} 11. a5 g6 12. Qb3 Qe7 13. Rae1 O-O
14. Nf4 Kg7 {Black has a very good game - the next move by White makes matters
much worse for him.} 15. g3 $2 h4 $19 16. Kg2 (16. Nd3 Bd7 17. Qc2 hxg3 18.
hxg3 Rh8 $19) 16... Bd7 17. Be2 Rab8 18. Bf3 Rh8 19. Na4 g5 20. Nd3 Be6 21. Qc3
g4 22. Bd1 Bd5+ 23. Kg1 hxg3 24. fxg3 Rxh2 25. e4 (25. Kxh2 Rh8+ 26. Kg1 Rh1+
27. Kf2 Rh2+ 28. Kg1 Rg2+ 29. Kh1 Qe4 {and mate in a few moves.}) 25... Nxe4
26. Nf4 Rbh8 27. Nxd5 Rh1+ {0-1 (27), guest-hellenikos, blitz game.}) (6... O-O
$1 7. Ne2 (7. Nc3 f5 $1 8. Qc2 Nd7 9. O-O-O {Castling queenside is very risky.}
Nf6 10. Nge2 a6 11. h3 g6 12. g4 b5 $17 {0-1 (27) Williams,S (2457)-Sargissian,
G (2690) Douglas 2014}) 7... f5 8. g3 $6 Nd7 9. Qc2 Nf6 10. Nbc3 c6 11. O-O Bd7
12. Rad1 ({In case of} 12. Nf4 {we can even take this knight} Bxf4 (12... g6
13. Rad1 h5 $4 14. Nxg6 $18 {would be a way to blunder.}) ({or just} 12... Qe7)
13. gxf4 Qe7 {and have a good game.} 14. Rad1 Be6 15. Bd3 g6 {White's king may
turn out weak in the long-term.}) 12... Qe7 13. d5 $6 c5 $1 {Is almost always
the right answer to d5. Black is already better - the d5-pawn is safely
blockaded and also takes away squares from the White pieces.} 14. a4 (14. Bb5
Bc8 {Here this is also playable, but White has} 15. Bd3 {attacking f5} g6 {
followed by} 16. Nb5 {Still Black's position is fully satisfactory after} Bd7 (
16... Ne8 $6 17. Nxd6 Nxd6 $2 {We would like to take with the knight, but it's
not possible due to} (17... Qxd6 $11) 18. Qxc5 $16) 17. Nxd6 Qxd6 $15) 14... g6
15. Bb5 Bc8 {Anyway Black has a good position, but I like this move best!
Black intends ...a6 and going back to d7.} 16. Rfe1 a6 17. Bc4 Bd7 18. a5 h5 {
Since the knight is on e2 instead of f3, this move gains in strength.} 19. Nf4
h4 $1 $17 (19... Kg7 $17)) 7. Nc3 f5 (7... O-O 8. Qc2 c6 9. Nf3 f5 (9... g6 10.
h4) 10. O-O Nf6) 8. Nf3 (8. g3 Nf6 9. Nge2 h5 10. h4 c6 11. Nf4 g6 12. Qf3 Kf8
13. O-O Kg7 14. Rad1 Re8 {see MODEL GAME 0-1 (51) LDago3 (2184)-hellenikos 
(2374)/Chess.com 2015..}) 8... O-O 9. Qc2 Nf6 (9... c6 10. Qxf5 $4 Ne5 $19) 10.
O-O c6 11. Rac1 ({or} 11. Rfd1 {with similar play. For example} Qe7 12. Rac1
Bd7 13. d5 c5 14. g3 (14. Nb5 Bxb5 15. Bxb5 g6 16. a4 a6 17. Bc4 Rfe8 18. a5 h5
(18... Ne4) 19. g3 Ne4) (14. Bb5 Bc8 15. Bd3 g6 16. Nb5 b6 17. Nxd6 Qxd6 18.
Bc4 Bd7) 14... g6 15. Bb5 Bc8) 11... Bd7 12. Rfd1 (12. Ne5 Bxe5 13. dxe5 Ng4)
12... Qe7 13. a3 g6 (13... Rfe8 14. Ng5) {What should we play after} 14. d5 {?}
{In almost any case, our move will be} c5 {Though here 14...Rac8 is also good.
White's passed pawn is safely blockaded. It also takes away squares from
White's pieces.} 15. Nb5 Bxb5 (15... Bb8 $2 16. d6) 16. Bxb5 {Black is better
after this exchange. White's passer is immobile, while Black can push his pawn
majority on the queenside.} a6 ({Let's suppose that we do not play ...a6-b5
and play} 16... Ne4 {instead} 17. a4 a6 18. Bc4 Rfe8 19. a5 {This is an
"unhealthy" fixing of our structure. The a5-pawn will be very vulnerable, e.g.
it will be captured in any endgame. Additionally, White has no pawn breaks.
What to play with Black?} h5 {I like this move - at good moment we will
advance the h-pawn further. ...h5 wins some space and keeps our structure
intact.} (19... g5 $6 {is premature - we weaken our light squares too much.}
20. Bd3 $36) 20. g3 (20. h4 {weakens g4, which may be used by our knight.}) (
20. h3 {Now we have various ideas.} g5 {with the idea ...g4, is one option,
while fixing the kingside with} (20... h4 {is another.})) 20... Kg7 {[%cal
Ye8h8,Yh5h4]}) 17. Be2 b5 $15 *

