{In this game, we will see the Mamedyarov plan in the Trompowsky! We must be
careful with our move order: when we see the move Bd3, WE MUST MAKE SURE THAT
WHTE IS NOT ABLE TO PLAY A FAST Qf3 followed by g4! To prevent this, we need
to postpone castling for a while! Look how Black was crushed in this game!} 1.
d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 d5 3. Bxf6 exf6 4. e3 c6 5. Bd3 {BE CAREFUL WHEN YOU SEE Bd3!
This introduces the Mamedyarov plan, White plays Bd3-Qf3-Nd2-Ne2 and
afterwards wants to attack with the kingside pawns, e.g. g4-h4. We need to
understand how to stop this plan!} Bd6 6. Nd2 O-O $6 {After premature castling,
White's plan works perfectly.} 7. Qf3 Na6 (7... Nd7 8. g4 {Black already
starts feeling the pressure.} Re8 9. h4 g6 10. Ne2 (10. h5 $16) 10... b5 11. h5
g5 12. h6 $16 {[%cal Ye2g3,Yg3f5]}) 8. c3 $1 Nc7 (8... g6 9. g4 Qd7 (9... Nc7
10. Ne2 Ne6 11. h4) 10. h3) 9. Ne2 g6 10. g4 $1 (10. O-O-O $2 f5 $1 {Now,
after ...f6-f5!, it is far more difficult to break Black's defences! A general
rule: if Black manages to play ...f5 against the setup with Bd3-Qf3, he is
always better!}) 10... c5 $2 (10... Ne6 11. h4 $16) 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. h4 $18 (
12. O-O-O $1 Be6 13. Nb3 Be7 14. Nbd4 $18 {after 10...c5? ...the Nd2 found a
wonderfull place on d4!}) 12... b5 13. h5 Ne6 14. Nf4 Nxf4 15. Qxf4 b4 16. Qh6
Qc7 17. hxg6 fxg6 18. Bxg6 {We saw that Black may end up very fast in a lost
position after a few inaccurate moves!} 1-0

