1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 d5 3. e3 $5 {A playable alternative which nevertheless does
not cause any problems! We play 3...c6!, giving White one last chance to
transpose to the ...Bxf6-ef6 structures. If he does not accept, we continue
with ...Bg4! and then ...Nbd7 followed by e6 or e5!} c6 $1 (3... c5 4. Bxf6
gxf6) 4. Bd3 Bg4 $1 5. Ne2 Nbd7 6. f3 (6. Nd2 e5 $36) 6... Bh5 7. Nbc3 (7. Nf4
$6 Bg6 8. Nxg6 hxg6 {Black has a great game, because White has created a lot
of weaknesses by playing f3.} 9. Nd2 e5 $132) 7... e5 $1 $132 8. Qd2 (8. O-O
Be7 9. Ng3 Bg6 $15 10. Nf5 Bxf5 11. Bxf5 O-O {Black stands perfectly here -
White's pair of bishops is irrelevant and he has seriously weakened his
position with f3, moreover, the knight stands badly on c3!}) 8... Be7 9. Ng3
Bg6 10. Nf5 Bxf5 11. Bxf5 O-O 12. O-O Re8 {Black got a satisfactory position
from the opening and later even managed to win the game!} 13. Rae1 Qc7 14. Kh1
Bd6 (14... Nb6 $15) 15. Ne2 g6 16. Bh3 exd4 17. exd4 Nh5 18. g3 Ng7 19. b3 Ne6
20. Be3 Nf6 21. c4 b6 22. Bg1 Re7 23. Bg2 Rae8 24. f4 a5 25. Nc3 Bb4 26. a3
Bxc3 27. Qxc3 Ng7 28. cxd5 Nxd5 29. Qc1 Rxe1 30. Rxe1 Rxe1 31. Qxe1 Qd6 32. Qe5
