1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {2.Nc3 introduces the Veresov Opening. White is ready to
occupy the center with e2-e4 and in reply to ...d7-d5 develops his queen's
bishop to f4 or g5. White's knight on c3 is misplaced from a strategic point
of view, since it blocks the c-pawn. The first player typically looks for fast
development and active piece play to compensate this positional shortcoming.}
d5 3. Bf4 {This move, popularized by GM Baadur Jobava, who won many excellent
games with it, is the reason why the Veresov (or Jobava System as 3.Bf4 is
justifyably called) has become popular again. As with 3.Bg5, White aims for
fast development, but by putting the bishop on f4, Nb5 becomes a tricky option.
} (3. Bg5 $6 {The "old" main line - engines point out that Black is more than
fine after this. It still can be used as a surprise weapon and in faster time
controls, but it's no longer theoretically relevant.} {We are going two
reliable moves:} h6 $1 ({and} 3... c6 $1)) {We will analyse the rare, but sound
} 3... Bd7 $5 {stopping any Nb5 ideas and planning to continue with ...e6-c5,
etc.} ({And as a second option the more theoretical} 3... c5 4. e3 cxd4 5. exd4
Bg4 $1 {provoking} 6. f3 {and simply returning with} Bd7 $1 {Black has a solid
position, while the weaknesses created by f3 offer good counterchances in the
long run.}) *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2024.06.10"]
[Round "?"]
[White "VERESOV 3.Bf4 Bd7"]
[Black "THEORETICAL OVERVIEW"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D00"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "34"]
[EventDate "2024.06.10"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 (2. Bf4 e6 3. Nc3 $6 {BE CAREFUL! This is a mistaken, but
very common move order. Now we do not play ...d5, but ...Bb4!, already with a
small advantage for Black !!!} Bb4 $1 $15 4. e3 Bxc3+ $1 (4... Nd5 $1 5. Nge2
Nxf4 6. exf4 d5 $15) 5. bxc3 d6 6. Nf3 Nbd7 $36) 2... d5 3. Bf4 Bd7 $5 {
An interesting continuation - it's rarely played but appears to be very good!
We stop any Nb5 ideas (we will capture the knight) and want to continue with ..
.e6-c5 and maybe Qb6, or ...Bc6-Nbd7 etc. with an easy game. White can try a
few brutal attempts but these simply backfire!} (3... e6 {is possible, though
we must avoid the trap} 4. e3 c5 $2 5. Nb5 $1 $14 {After forcing our knight to
a6, it's very hard to get rid of the knight on b5.}) 4. e3 {The most natural
move.} ({We have to check the gambit} 4. e4 $6 {, though it does not work too
well:} dxe4 5. f3 Bc6 {Black makes use of having played ...Bd7.} 6. Bc4 e6 7.
Nxe4 Nxe4 8. fxe4 Bd6 $3 (8... Bxe4 9. Qe2 $132) 9. e5 Bb4+ 10. Kf1 Nd7 $15 11.
Nf3 Be7) (4. Qd2 $6 e6 5. e3 ({After} 5. O-O-O $2 b5 $3 $17 {Black is
immediately better.} 6. e3 b4 $1 (6... a6 {is also good.}) 7. Nb5 Na6 $17 {
Black will castle (...Be7, ...0-0), play ...c5 at some point and have a much
safer king.}) 5... c5 6. Nb5 {In this line, we will often take this knight and
play ...Nc6 with good play. Here 6...Na6 is even stronger! Qd2 does not
combine well with Nb5, since White's queen is about to get hit by ...Ne4.} (6.
Nf3 Nc6 7. a3 a6 $15) 6... Na6 $3 7. f3 (7. c3 c4 $17 8. a4 Qa5) 7... Qb6 8. a4
c4 {White gets pushed back.}) 4... e6 5. Nf3 (5. g4 $6 Bb4 $1 6. Bg2 (6. f3 c5
$15) 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Bb5 $3 $15 8. g5 (8. Rb1 Ba6) 8... Ne4) (5. Nb5 Bxb5 6.
Bxb5+ c6 $11 {see MODEL GAME ½-½ (47) Stanisz,P (2199)-Mrozowski,P (2116)
Jastrzebia Gora 2022.} (6... Nbd7 $11)) 5... c5 (5... Bb4 {The bishop on b4
might turn out to be misplaced on b4 after} 6. Nd2 $5) 6. Nb5 $1 (6. a3 a6 $1 (
6... Qb6 $1 7. Rb1 Bd6 8. dxc5 Qxc5 $11 9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. Bd3 Bc6 $3 $15) (6...
Bc6 7. Nb5 $36) 7. Bd3 (7. Be2 Bc6 $1 8. Ne5 (8. O-O Nbd7 $15 (8... Bd6 9. Ne5
O-O {see MODEL GAME, 0-1 (55) Jaskolka,T (2238)-Kourkoulos Arditis,S (2539)
Chess.com INT 2023.})) 8... Nfd7 $5 {I really like this move - by keeping the
knight on b8, Black can answer Nxc6 with ...Nxc6!} 9. O-O (9. Nxc6 Nxc6 $15 {
We are threatening ...cxd4 and ...Qb6.}) 9... Nxe5 10. Bxe5 Nd7 11. Bg3 Be7 12.
Qd2 O-O $15 {White does not have any logical plan, whereas we are about to
start playing on the queenside with ...b5.}) 7... Qb6 (7... Bc6 {is another
interesting option.} 8. O-O Nbd7 {Black is fine - White has no attacking
chances, since we didn't play ...cxd4 and we are about to play ...c4.} 9. h3 c4
10. Be2 b5 $15) 8. Rb1 Bd6 $11) (6. Ne5 $2 {is totally pointless!} Nc6 $1 $15
7. Be2 (7. Nxc6 Bxc6 8. Be2 c4 9. O-O Be7 $15) (7. Nxd7 Qxd7 $15) 7... cxd4 (
7... Be7 8. O-O O-O $15) 8. exd4 Qb6 9. Nxc6 Bxc6 10. Rb1 Bb4 $15 (10... Be7
$15)) (6. Be2 a6 (6... Qb6 7. O-O a6 8. Rb1 Be7 $11) 7. O-O Bc6 8. Ne5 Be7 {
followed by ...0-0, ...Nfd7!? and an equal game.}) 6... Bxb5 {It's best to
take the knight.} (6... Na6 $6 7. a4 $14 {and it's not easy to get rid of the
annoying knight on b5.}) 7. Bxb5+ Nbd7 $132 {Black has a healthy position with
good play. White's pair of bishops is not a big deal, since our remaining
bishop is strong and we have good central control.} 8. c3 (8. Ne5 $4 Qa5+ $19)
8... a6 9. Bd3 Be7 $11 (9... Qb6 $1 10. Rb1 Bd6 $11) 10. Ne5 (10. O-O O-O 11.
Qe2 b5) 10... Nxe5 (10... O-O 11. O-O Qb6 $1 12. Rb1 Bd6 $11) 11. dxe5 Nd7 12.
O-O Qc7 $36 13. Bg3 h5 $15 14. f4 h4 15. Bf2 c4 16. Bc2 h3 17. g3 O-O-O $17 *

