[EventDate "2024.06.10"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 {The main theoretical move.} 4. e3 (4. e4 $5 {
A playable alternative.} Nxe4 $1 5. Nxe4 (5. Bb5+ $6 {This is bad, but we must
know the right answer 5...Nc6!=/+ and avoid 5...Bd7?? 6.Nxd5!+-.} Nc6 $1 (5...
Bd7 $4 6. Nxd5 $3 $18 Qa5+ 7. c3 Bxb5 8. Nc7+ Kd7 9. Nxa8 $18) 6. Nxe4 dxe4 7.
Ne2 (7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. dxc5 Qa5+ $17) 7... e6 $15 (7... Bg4) 8. O-O Bd7 $15)
5... dxe4 6. dxc5 (6. d5 g6 7. Ne2 Bg7 8. Nc3 Qb6 9. Rb1 O-O) 6... Qxd1+ $1 {
A simple line - we just play an endgame with chances for both sides! The
better endgame player will prevail!} (6... Qa5+ $1 {This is another good
alternative! Besides 6...Qxd1+, this is another simple and good alternative!}
7. c3 Qxc5 8. Qa4+ Nc6 9. Qxe4 g6 10. Nf3 (10. Bc4 Bg7 11. Rd1 (11. Be3 Qa5)
11... O-O $132) (10. Be3 Qa5 11. Bc4 Bg7 $132) 10... Bg7 11. Bc4 (11. Be2 $4
Bxc3+ $19) 11... Bf5 12. Qe2 O-O $132) (6... Nd7 $13) 7. Rxd1 Nc6 8. Bb5 (8. f3
Bf5 $1 9. c3 (9. Bc4 $2 e6 $17) 9... e6 10. b4 Be7 $132) (8. Be3 g6 $5 (8... e5
9. Bc4 f5 $132) (8... Bd7 $132) 9. Ne2 Bg7 $132) 8... f6 $1 {After this strong
move, followed by ...e5, Black is already better.} 9. Ne2 e5 10. Be3 Be6 11.
Nc3 (11. O-O a6 (11... Rc8 $15) 12. Ba4 Kf7 $15) 11... f5 $15 {0-1 (45)
Bortnyk,O (2605)-Praggnanandhaa,R (2690) Chess.com INT 2023}) (4. Nb5 $2 Qa5+ {
and White is forced to retreat with his knight.} 5. Nc3 cxd4 6. Qxd4 Nc6 $19 {
is a disaster for White.}) 4... cxd4 5. exd4 (5. Nb5 $2 {is still premature as
the complications after} Qa5+ {favour Black:} 6. Qd2 (6. c3 dxc3 $1 7. Nc7+ (7.
Nxc3 g6 $17) 7... Kd8 $19) 6... Qxd2+ 7. Kxd2 g5 $3 (7... dxe3+ 8. Bxe3 Na6 $17
{is also good enough.}) 8. Be5 dxe3+ 9. fxe3 Ne4+ 10. Ke1 f6 11. Bd4 Na6 $17 {
with a big advantage for Black.}) 5... Bg4 $1 {We provoke the weakening move
f3 and then return to d7!} (5... Nc6 $4 6. Nb5 Qa5+ 7. c3) (5... a6 {is the
usual move, with lots of theory.}) 6. f3 (6. Qd2 Nc6 7. f3 (7. h3 Bh5 $15) (7.
Nb5 $2 {can simply be met with} Rc8 $17) 7... Bd7 8. Nb5 Rc8 9. Qe2 $2 {
Creates a mating threat - however if Black sees it, then this move is simply a
loss of time.} e6 $17 (9... a6 $4 10. Nd6#) 10. c3 Qb6 11. Nd6+ Bxd6 12. Bxd6
Nxd4) (6. Be2 $5 {SOS - BE CAREFUL! This innocent-looking move contains a
deadly trap!} Bxe2 7. Qxe2 (7. Ncxe2 Nc6 8. c3 e6) 7... a6 $3 {Preventing Nb5!}
(7... Nc6 $4 8. Nb5 Rc8 9. Nd6+ {Don't become one of the players who fell for
this trick!}) 8. O-O-O (8. g4 $5 h6 9. O-O-O e6 10. h4 Nc6 $13 {see MODEL GAME
0-1 (56) Erigaisi,A (2712)-Keymer,V (2717) Kolkata IND 2023.}) 8... Nc6 9. Nf3
e6 $15 10. Ne5 Rc8) (6. Nf3 $2 {is totally meaningless!} Nc6 7. Be2 e6 $15)
6... Bd7 $1 7. Qd2 (7. Qe2 $6 {Setting a trap.} a6 $1 (7... Nc6 $2 8. Nb5 $1
Rc8 $2 (8... e5 $142 $16) 9. Nd6#) 8. O-O-O (8. g4 {is not dangerous - if
White plays g4-g5, we can play ...Nh5.} e6 9. g5 Nh5 10. Bd2 Nc6 $17) 8... b5
$15 9. g4 b4 10. Nb1 Bb5) (7. Nb5 Bxb5 8. Bxb5+ Nc6 9. c3 e6 {Once again,
Black has a great game! While the pair of bishops is irrelevant (the remaining
black bishop is very powerful), White has weakened his structure with f3!} 10.
Ne2 (10. Bxc6+ bxc6) 10... Bd6 $132) (7. g4 e6 ({or} 7... a6 8. g5 $6 Nh5 9.
Nxd5 $4 Qa5+ $19) 8. Qd2 a6 (8... Nc6 $132) 9. O-O-O Nc6 10. Nge2 b5 {Black is
already better - his attack is more dangerous.}) (7. Bd3 e6 8. Nge2 a6 9. O-O
Nc6 10. a3 b5 {Black has good play - the c3-knight and f3-pawn are badly
placed. For example} 11. Qd2 Be7 12. Kh1 O-O 13. Nd1 b4 14. a4 a5 15. Nf2 Bc8
$5 16. Rae1 Ba6 17. Bxa6 Rxa6 18. Nd3 Ra8 $15) 7... e6 8. g4 Nc6 ({or} 8... a6)
(8... Qb6 {see MODEL GAMES 0-1 (52) Timofeev,A (2567)-Keymer,V (2690) chess.
com INT 2023 and 0-1 (31) Caruana,F (2791)-So,W (2772) Chess.com INT 2021.}) 9.
O-O-O a6 {Black gets very good counterplay on the queenside, for example} 10.
Nge2 b5 (10... Bb4) 11. Ng3 h6 *

