1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 cxd4 5. exd4 Bg4 6. f3 Bd7 7. g4 e6 8. h4
Nc6 (8... a6) (8... Qb6) 9. Nge2 Qb6 10. Rb1 {Now White's king remains stuck
in the center.} ({White should play} 10. Qd2 {sacrificing the b2-pawn - Black
probably cannot even take it.} Rc8 $15) 10... Rc8 11. a3 Be7 12. h5 {With the
idea to prevent ...Nh5 after g4-g5.} (12. g5 Nh5) 12... h6 {Black defends
against g4-g5.} 13. Qd2 Na5 14. Nc1 Bd6 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. Kf2 O-O 17. g5 ({
After} 17. Be2 {Black strikes in the center} e5 18. dxe5 Qxe5 {After} 19. f4 $2
{Black can even play.} Qxc3 $5 {, though probably simply retreating with the
queen is stronger - White's king is simply too exposed.}) 17... hxg5 18. Qxg5
Nh7 19. Qg2 Qf4 20. N1e2 Qf6 {Black's king is well-protected and he will
exploit the weaknesses in White's position.} 21. h6 g6 22. Qg3 Nc4 23. Qf4 b5
24. Qxf6 Nxf6 $17 {Black's advantage persists in the endgame. White has static
pawn weaknesses - f3 and h6.} 25. Nf4 a5 26. Nd3 Rfd8 27. Nc5 Be8 28. Bxc4 bxc4
29. Nb7 Rd7 30. Nxa5 Ra7 31. h7+ Kh8 32. Ne2 Rxa5 33. c3 Rb5 34. Ke3 Rcb8 35.
