1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 $6 {This move was considered to be interesting
about 20 years ago! The computers of today are of a different opinion!} h6 $1 {
A simple and lazy option! Equally good is 3...c6!} (3... c6 $1 4. Bxf6 (4. Qd2
Nbd7 5. f3 (5. O-O-O b5 $17) 5... b5 6. a3 h6 7. Bxf6 (7. Bh4 e5 8. e3 Bd6 $17)
7... exf6 8. e4 Nb6 $15) (4. Qd3 Nbd7 (4... g6) 5. O-O-O (5. f3 e5 $17) 5... b5
$17) (4. f3 $6 Nbd7 5. e4 dxe4 6. fxe4 e5 7. dxe5 Qa5 $1 $15 8. Bxf6 gxf6 (8...
Ba3 $5) 9. e6 fxe6 $15) (4. e3 Qb6 ({or simply} 4... Nbd7) 5. Rb1 Bg4 $11 (5...
Bf5 $11)) (4. Nf3 $6 Ne4 $1 5. Nxe4 dxe4 6. Ng1 Qb6 $15 7. Bc1 e5 8. e3 Be6 9.
Ne2 Nd7 10. Nc3 f5 11. Be2 Rd8 12. g4 Nf6 13. gxf5 Bxf5 14. Bd2 exd4 15. exd4
Rxd4 16. Qc1 Bc5 17. Be3 O-O 18. Rg1 Rd7 19. Bxc5 Qxc5 20. Qe3 Qb4 21. Rb1 Nd5
22. Qd2 e3 23. fxe3 Qh4+ 24. Rg3 Nb4 25. Bd3 Bxd3 26. cxd3 Nxd3+ 27. Kd1 Nf2+ {
0-1 Papenin,N-Tanriverdi,E/Marmaris 2019/EXT 2020}) 4... exf6 {Resembles a bad
version of the Trompowsky - White's knight is misplaced on c3, since he would
very much like to play c2-c4. For example} 5. e3 f5 6. Bd3 g6 7. Nf3 Bd6 8. O-O
Nd7 9. Ne2 Nf6 10. c4 dxc4 11. Bxc4 O-O 12. Nc3 Kg7 13. Rb1 Qe7 $1 {We don't
want to play ...a5, since we want to keep the option to play ...c5 in reply to
b2-b4-b5. Moreover it's useful to provoke a3:} ({Let's compare this to} 13...
Bd7 14. b4 Qe7 {Now} 15. b5 {is possible since there is no pawn hanging on a3.}
) 14. a3 Bd7 15. b4 {Firstly, White's pawns are immobile, since he cannot play
b4-b5 as a3 would be hanging. Secondly, we can directly attack the
a3-b4-formation with} b5 $1 16. Bd3 a5 $1 $17 {and White cannot avoid losing a
pawn.}) 4. Bxf6 (4. Bh4 c6 5. e3 Bf5 $132 (5... Nbd7 $132)) 4... exf6 $132 {
Black has a good version of the Trompowsky - due to the misplaced knight on c3,
we can even invest a full tempo in provoking White to take on f6!} 5. e3 (5. e4
$6 Bb4 6. exd5 Qxd5 7. Nge2 (7. Qe2+ Be6 $15) 7... O-O 8. Qd3 Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 Nc6
$15 {White has fallen behind in development and cannot even castle because a2
would hang.}) 5... c6 6. Bd3 (6. Nf3 Nd7 $132) 6... f5 7. Qf3 $2 {This
resembles the Mamedyarov-idea in the Trompowsky, however the queen will turn
out to be misplaced on f3.} (7. Nge2 Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. Nb1 {White prepares
c2-c4.} g6 10. Nd2 Nd7 11. c4 dxc4 12. Nxc4 Bc7 $15 {[%cal Yd7f6] The pair of
bishops offers good long-term prospects for Black.}) 7... g6 8. Nge2 h5 9. h3
Nd7 10. O-O-O Nf6 11. Kb1 Bd6 $17 (11... b5 $5) 12. g4 $6 {White tries to
activate his game by sacrificing a pawn, but his idea does not work.} fxg4 13.
hxg4 Nxg4 (13... Bxg4 14. Qg2 Qe7 15. f3 Bd7 16. e4 dxe4 17. fxe4 Ng4 $19 {
Black is going to castle long, with a winning position.}) 14. e4 dxe4 15. Nxe4
Be6 16. N2c3 O-O 17. Qg2 Bf4 18. Nc5 Bc8 19. d5 Qe7 20. N5e4 Kg7 21. Rhe1 Qh4
22. Qg1 Qh2 23. Qf1 Bf5 24. Re2 Qh4 25. Qg1 Ne5 26. f3 Nxf3 27. Qc5 Bg4 28. Rf1
Be5 29. dxc6 b6 30. Qb4 Nd4 31. Ref2 Nxc6 32. Qb5 Rac8 33. a3 Qe7 34. Nd5 Qb7
35. Nef6 Nd4 36. Qb4 Rc5 37. Be4 Qb8 38. Qd2 {0-1 Morozevich,A-Leko,P/Abu
Dhabi 2019.} *

