1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 {This move introduces the flexible Colle System.
White has many possible options to develop his pieces. For example -
developing the bishops to d3 and b2 with or without c4 - developing the
queen's knight to d2 or c3 - play Bd3, 0-0, c3, Nbd2 and so on...} b6 {This is
a fine move - we don't want to strike immediately in the center with d5 or c5.
First, we see how White arranges his pieces, and then we decide which setup to
choose! SOS! WE DO NOT NEED TO KNOW ANY CONCRETE THEORY IN THIS LINE! WE JUST
HAVE TO KNOW WHERE TO PUT OUR PIECES, DEPENDING ON WHITE'S SETUP!} ({Playing a
setup} 3... c5 $5 {analogous to our proposed repertoire against the London
System and Torre Attack, does not fully work if White knows what he is doing:}
4. Bd3 cxd4 5. exd4 Be7 {Black hopes for Bf4 or Bg5, when we could play a
Hedgehog setup.} 6. c4 $1 b6 7. O-O Bb7 8. Nc3 d5 (8... O-O 9. d5 $1) 9. cxd5
Nxd5 10. Ne5 $1 {This is considered risky for Black - see also the line given
after 5...c5.} O-O 11. Qg4 Nf6 12. Qh4 {Here, the natural} Nc6 {is already a
losing mistake!} 13. Bg5 g6 14. Ba6 $3 $18) (3... d5 {is maybe the best move
objectively, though it's a bit passive in my opinion.}) 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O g6 $5
{This double-edged idea is my recommendation - we want to trick White! Instead
of playing ...Be7-d5-c5-dc4-ed4-Re8-Bf8-g6-Bg7, we want to give him hanging
pawns in the center and immediately develop the Bishop to g7, winning several
tempi! Of course, in order to do that, we allow him to play a Nc3-Bd3-e3-e4
setup. Then we go ...d6-Nc6-e5, reaching some kind of King's Indian Defence.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
