1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 b6 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O g6 $5 {A very nice and
double-edged idea - we want to trick White! Instead of playing ...
Be7-d5-c5-dc4-ed4-Re8-Bf8-g6-Bg7, we want to give him hanging pawns in the
center and immediately develop the Bishop to g7, winning several tempi! Of
course, in order to do that, we allow him to play a Nc3-Bd3-e3-e4 setup. Then
we go ...d6-Nc6-e5, reaching some kind of King's Indian Defence. Of course,
the computer never likes this, but it is in fact quite unclear!} (5... d5 $5 {
is very solid but passive!} 6. Nbd2 Be7 (6... Bd6 7. b3 Nbd7 8. Bb2 O-O 9. Ne5)
7. c4 (7. b3 O-O 8. Bb2) 7... O-O 8. b3 dxc4 9. bxc4 c5 10. Bb2 Nc6 11. Qe2
cxd4 12. exd4 Nb4 13. Bb1 Re8 14. a3 Nc6 15. Bd3 Bf8 16. Rfe1 g6 17. Rad1 Bg7 {
With 5...g6, we want to reach a position like this, but save time on the
manoeuvre ...Be7-Re8-Bf8-g6-Bg7!}) (5... c5 6. c4 $1 {This is the problem!} (6.
b3 g6 $1 $132 (6... Be7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2 cxd4 9. exd4 Nc6 10. c4 d5 11. Rc1
dxc4 12. bxc4 Re8)) 6... cxd4 7. exd4 Be7 8. Nc3 d5 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Ne5 $1 $14
O-O 11. Qg4 $1 Nf6 12. Qh4 $36) 6. c4 $5 (6. b3 $6 {A VERY IMPORTANT LINE..AND
A VERY IMPORTANT SETUP THAT CAN BE REACHED VIA VARIOUS MOVE ORDERS! Pay a lot
of attention to the lines and setups - most Colle players will play something
like this over the board when our setup with ...g6 works perfectly!} Bg7 7. Bb2
O-O 8. Nbd2 c5 $1 (8... d5) 9. Re1 (9. c4 cxd4 10. exd4 d5 $1 11. Rc1 Nc6 12.
Re1 (12. c5 $2 Nd7 $3 $17) 12... Rc8 (12... dxc4 $5 13. Nxc4 Nb4 $3 14. Ba3 (
14. Bb1 Bh6 15. Ne3 Nfd5 $15 16. a3 Nxe3 17. fxe3 Nd5) 14... a5 $1 $15) 13. Qe2
dxc4 14. bxc4 Re8 $15 15. h3 Re7 16. Qe3 Rd7 $15 (16... Rec7 $15) 17. a3 Ne8)
9... d5 10. c4 cxd4 11. exd4 Nc6 {We already know that we have a very good
position. Compared to setups with ...Be7, where Black later often plays ...
Re8-Bf8-g6-Bg7, our bishop IS already on g7! For example} 12. Rc1 (12. h3 Re8
13. Rc1 dxc4 14. bxc4 Re7 $3 15. Qe2 Rc8 16. Bb1 Ba6 $15 (16... Nh5 $15) (16...
Rd7 $15)) (12. c5 $6 Nd7 $3 {White cannot maintain his pawn on c5.} 13. cxb6
Qxb6 {The best way to recapture; the knight would be misplaced on b6. Moreover
White has trouble to defend d4.} 14. Nf1 Nxd4 $19) 12... Rc8 13. Bf1 dxc4 (
13... Re8 14. Ne5 Ne4 15. cxd5 exd5 16. Ndf3 Nxe5 17. Nxe5 Qh4 $13 {0-1 Cori
Tello,J-Saldano Dayer,H/Buenos Aires 2011.}) 14. Nxc4 {Black has a good
version of an IQP position.} Re8 15. Ba3 (15. Nfe5 Nd5 16. Nd2 Nce7 $15) 15...
Bf8 16. Bxf8 Rxf8 $15) (6. Nbd2 $5 d5 $5 {Here ...d5 is more interesting as
White has put his knight on d2! Our main goal is once again to reach a
position with hanging pawns!} (6... Bg7 $5 7. e4 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. Re1 c5 $132)
7. b3 Bg7 8. Bb2 (8. c4 O-O 9. cxd5 Nxd5 $3 10. Bb2 c5) 8... O-O 9. c4 c5 10.
Qe2 (10. cxd5 Nxd5 $3 $15) (10. dxc5 $1 bxc5 11. Rc1 Nbd7 12. Qe2 Re8 $132)
10... cxd4 11. exd4 (11. Bxd4 $1 Nc6 12. Bb2 $11) 11... dxc4 12. bxc4 Nc6 13.
Rfd1 Re8 14. Rac1 Rc8 15. Bb1 Re7 $1 $15 (15... Nh5 $1 $15)) 6... Bg7 7. Nc3 {
This is the best plan for White against the ...b6-g6 Variation!} (7. b3 $6 {
Once again we go for the typical positions!} O-O 8. Bb2 c5 $1 (8... d5 $5 9.
cxd5 Nxd5 $1 $132 {SOS! IN SUCH POSITIONS WE ALMOST ALWAYS TAKE BACK WITH THE
KNIGHT ON d5!}) 9. Nbd2 cxd4 10. exd4 d5 11. Rc1 dxc4 12. bxc4 Nc6 (12... Nbd7
13. Qe2) 13. Re1 (13. Ne4 Nxd4 $19 (13... Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Na5 (14... Rc8))) 13...
Re8 14. Bb1 Rc8 15. Qe2 Re7 $1 $15 16. Qe3 Rd7 (16... Rec7)) 7... O-O $5 {
WE ARE ALREADY OUT OF BOOK HERE! This is an interesting King's Indian Defence
type of position, with our bishop a bit awkwardly placed on b7. On the other
hand, White's bishop should be put on e2, rather than d3, and his e4 push will
come in 2 moves (e3-e4).  Still, since it's a King's Indian, the computer
typically dislikes it from Black's point of view. But still, since it's a
King's Indian, the positions are unclear and double-edged!} (7... d5 $1 {
This is a more solid and less risky setup.} 8. cxd5 (8. b3 O-O 9. Bb2 dxc4 10.
bxc4 c5 $132) 8... exd5 9. b3 (9. b4 $5 O-O 10. Bb2 a6 11. a4 c6 $132 12. Rc1
Nbd7 13. Qb3 a5 $5 (13... b5 $5)) 9... O-O 10. Ba3 Re8 11. Rc1 c6 12. Qc2 Nbd7
$132) 8. e4 d6 {Now, quite often, our plan consists in playing ...Nc6 and ...
e6-e5! Here White can play pretty much everything:} 9. Bg5 (9. Bd2 Nc6 $1 10.
d5 (10. Re1 e5 11. d5 Ne7 12. b4 Nd7 13. Qc2 h6 $132) 10... Ne7 $132 11. Qc2
exd5 $1 (11... e5) 12. exd5 c6 13. dxc6 Nxc6 $132) (9. Re1 Nc6 10. Bf1 (10. d5
Nb4 $5 11. Bf1 a5 12. Bd2 (12. dxe6 fxe6 $132) 12... Na6 $1 (12... e5 13. a3
Na6 14. Rb1 Bc8 15. b4) 13. Rb1 (13. a3 Nc5 14. Qc2 (14. b4 axb4 15. axb4 Rxa1
16. Qxa1 Ncxe4 $19) 14... a4 $15) 13... Nc5 14. b3 exd5 $3 (14... c6 $3 $132
15. dxe6 Nxe6) 15. cxd5 (15. exd5 Bc8 $132) 15... c6 $132) (10. Bd2 e5 11. d5
Ne7 12. b4 Nd7 {[%cal Yh7h6,Yf7f5]}) 10... h6 (10... e5 11. d5 Ne7 12. Bd2 Nd7
(12... c6 13. b4) 13. b4 h6 14. Qc2 (14. a4 a5 15. bxa5 Rxa5 16. Nb5 Ra6 17. a5
Nc5 18. axb6 cxb6 19. Rxa6 Bxa6 20. Bb4 Bxb5 21. cxb5 Qc7) 14... f5 15. Rec1 f4
16. Ne1 c5 17. a3 g5 18. f3 Nf6 19. Nd3 h5 20. bxc5 bxc5 21. Rab1 Bc8 {By now,
Black has great play - ...g5-g4 is about to happen, whereas White does not
have any threats on the kingside yet.}) 11. Rb1 e5 12. d5 Ne7 13. b4 Nd7 (13...
c6) 14. Be3 f5 $132) (9. h3 Nc6 10. Be3 e5 11. d5 Ne7 12. b4 Nd7 13. Rc1 h6 {
followed by ...f5 with nice, unclear play.} ({But not} 13... f5 $2 14. Ng5 $1))
(9. Qc2 Nc6 10. a3 Nd7 11. Be3 e5 12. d5 Ne7 $132) 9... h6 $5 10. Bd2 Nc6 $1 (
10... Nbd7 $1 11. Re1 c5 (11... e5 $5 12. d5 Nh5 13. b4 Nf4 14. Bf1 f5) 12. d5
exd5 (12... e5 $1 $132) 13. exd5 $14) (10... e5 $5 11. d5 a5 $132) (10... c5 $1
{Another very interesting plan - to play with a totally blocked center!} 11. d5
e5 12. a3 Nh5 13. Qc1 Kh7 14. Ne1 Nd7 15. Be2 Nhf6 16. Nd3 Ba6 $5 17. b3 Ne8
18. Ra2 Qe7 19. Qc2 Nc7 20. a4 f5 21. f3 f4 22. Nb5 Nf6 23. b4 g5 24. bxc5 bxc5
25. Bc3 Ng8 26. Rd1 Ne8 27. Rb2 h5 28. Rdb1 Nh6 29. Na3 Nf6 30. Nb5 Nf7 31. Ba5
Rac8 32. Ne1 g4 33. Rb3 Bh6 34. R1b2 Rg8 35. Kh1 Rg7 36. Qb1 Bg5 37. Na3 Bh4
38. Rb8 Ng5 39. Rxc8 Bxc8 40. Rb8 Qd7 41. Nb5 Bxe1 42. Qxe1 gxf3 43. gxf3 {
0-1 Jodorcovsky,P-Delgado Ramirez,N/Asuncion PAR 2015}) 11. Re1 e5 12. d5 Ne7
13. b4 Nd7 14. Qc2 f5 $132 *

