1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 ({or} 2. Bf4) 2... e6 3. Bf4 {The London System,
characterized by the moves d4, (Nf3,) and Bf4, can be quite difficult to deal
with. White's setup is solid and at the same time contains some poison. For
instance, when Black develops in classical style with ...d5 etc., White gets a
nice outpost on e5 for his knight, and going along with that, some attacking
chances on the kingside.} c5 4. e3 cxd4 $1 {My proposed repertoire against the
London System is based on the so-called HEDGEHOG setup! We start by playing a
fast ...c5-cxd4! and then arrange our pieces according to the scheme ...
Be7-b6-Bb7-d6-Nbd7-0-0-a6 and ...Re8! (this moves can be played in various
order). For example} 5. exd4 b6 6. Nbd2 Bb7 7. Bd3 Be7 8. h3 d6 9. c3 Nbd7 10.
O-O O-O 11. Re1 Re8 12. a4 a6 {We have reached our desired setup and look for
counterchances in connection preparing ...b5 or in some cases ...e5. White on
the other hand, has no pawn breaks available and is limited to manoeuvering
with his pieces. A complicated strategic fight with chances for both sides
lies ahead.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "LONDON SYSTEM"]
[Black "THEORETICAL OVERVIEW"]
