[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "34"]
[EventDate "2024.06.09"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 (2. Bf4 e6 3. e3 ({After} 3. Nc3 Bb4 $1 {we get a nice Nimzo
Indian type of position.}) 3... c5 (3... b6 {is another playable system. Black
plays ...b6 and ...Bb7 first and only then ...c5. However, this gives White
more options.}) (3... d5 {which is of course a solid and playable setup, plays
into White's hands - he gets to play for example Nf3-e5, Bd3 etc.}) 4. c3 {
Now White is ready to take back on d4 with his c-pawn. We deal with this under
the header LONDON SYSTEM - EARLY c3.}) 2... e6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 (4. c3 {also
will be dealt with in LONDON SYSTEM - EARLY c3.}) 4... cxd4 $1 {Against the
London System, a very good setup is the so-called HEDGEHOG! We start by
playing a fast ...c5-cxd4! and then arrange our pieces according to the scheme
...Be7-b6-Bb7-d6-Nbd7-0-0-a6 and ...Re8! We play all these moves without
exception and can play them with many possible move orders!} 5. exd4 (5. Nxd4
$4 {is both a positional and a tactical mistake.} e5 $1 6. Bxe5 Qa5+ 7. Nc3
Qxe5 $19) 5... b6 6. Nbd2 Bb7 ({Another playable and good move is} 6... Ba6) 7.
Bd3 Be7 8. h3 {White will need this move at some point.} d6 {I like to
postpone castling.} 9. c3 Nbd7 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 Re8 (11... a6) 12. Bg3 {
White can play all sorts of moves like 12.Bg3, 12.Bh2, 12.a4, 12.Rc1, etc.
HERE CONCRETE THEORY DOES NOT MATTER AT ALL OF COURSE! ONLY PLANS AND IDEAS!
Here are some very nice sample variations which you will definitely face in
your games!} (12. Bh2 {In my opinion the bishop is worse on h2 compared to g3.
It takes away the escape square from White's king, which might become a factor
in later complications.}) 12... a6 {Now White has many options.} 13. Qe2 (13.
c4 {What to play against this?} d5 $1 {Now White would like to play c4-c3,
when he would be better! But then Black could answer ...d5-d6 :) Jokes aside,
after 13.c4 d5 Black gets a good version of an IQP position.} 14. Rc1 dxc4 15.
Nxc4 Rc8 $132) (13. Ne4 $6 {We already know what to do here! Exchange the
pieces and play ...b5.} Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Bxe4 15. Rxe4 Nf6 16. Re1 b5 {We are not
in a hurry to play ...d5.} 17. Qe2 Qd7 18. Rad1 Qb7 {I like this manoeuvre -
we are not in a hurry to play ...d5. The queen is well placed and supports ...
b4. We will play ...b4, when White cannot answer it with c3-c4. We probably
will prepare ...b4 with ...d5 (to take c4 under control). White's problem is
that he doesn't have an active plan and exchanging pieces with for example
Nd2-e4 only helps Black!} 19. Nd2 (19. Qe3 Rac8 20. Re2 b4 $17 {since there is
no c3-c4 for white} 21. cxb4 Qxb4 22. b3 a5) 19... Rac8 20. Ne4 Nxe4 21. Qxe4
Qxe4 22. Rxe4 d5 23. Re2 b4 $15 (23... a5) (23... Rc4)) (13. a4 {Another
important plan - this move can be played at several points.} Qc7 (13... Qc8 $5)
14. Qe2 {What to do now? Black cannot play ...Bc6 since the a6-pawn is hanging
and he can never move his a8-rook.} Qc8 $5 {This prepares ...Bc6, followed by .
..Qb7, and finally ...b5.} (14... a5 $2 {should of course be avoided.}) (14...
Bf8) 15. c4 {Now the usual move is ...d5. If we are afraid of Rc1, we can play}
(15. Nf1 Bc6) 15... Qd8 {intending ...d5.} 16. b4 (16. Rad1 Bf8 17. Nb1 d5 $132
) 16... a5 17. b5 {Since White has weakend his control over c5, Black can
again play for ...d5. The pawn moves a4 and b5 created a space advantage but
at the same time created some weaknesses.} ({After} 17. bxa5 Rxa5 18. Nb3 Ra7
$15 {White's a-pawn is weak.}) 17... Rc8 (17... d5) 18. Bh4 d5 19. Ne5 (19.
cxd5 Nxd5 $17) 19... Nxe5 20. dxe5 Nd7 21. Bxe7 Qxe7 22. cxd5 Bxd5 23. Ne4 {
Now of course e5 is hanging. Let's insert the moves f4 and ...Rc7 to show a
strategic idea:} Rc7 24. f4 {Black must play} Bxe4 $1 25. Qxe4 g6 $17 {White
remains with a lot of weaknesses. Our knight has a great square on c5.}) 13...
Qc7 {We are playing a waiting game and play useful waiting moves. In general
we look for the right moment to play ...b5.} (13... b5 $2 {is premature due to}
14. a4 $1 bxa4 15. Rxa4 $16 {[%csl Ra6]}) 14. Rad1 ({After} 14. Ne4 Nxe4 15.
Bxe4 Bxe4 16. Qxe4 Nf6 17. Qe2 b5 {is already possible.} 18. a4 Qb7 $11 {
At some moment we will play ...d5 and ...b4.}) (14. c4 Qd8 $5 {We want to play
...d5 and unpin our d-pawn.} (14... Bf8 $5 {Now ...e5 becomes an option.}) 15.
Rad1 d5 $1 {We are not claiming to be better but we have a playable and
unclear position. For example} 16. Ne5 {[%cal Ye5f7]} ({After} 16. b3 {we will
at some point take on c4 and saddle White with hanging pawns. For example} Nf8
17. Ne5 Bb4 {(an annoying little move)} 18. Rf1 Rc8) 16... Nf8 (16... dxc4 $2
17. Nxf7 $1 cxd3 (17... Kxf7 18. Qxe6+ Kf8 19. Bxc4 $18) 18. Qxe6 $16) (16...
Nxe5 $2 17. dxe5 Nd7 18. cxd5 Bxd5 19. Bxa6 $16)) ({What to do if White waits
with} 14. a3 $5 Bf8 {We prepare ...e5 or ...g6, ...Bg7.} ({We don't play} 14...
h6 $2 {since it weakens the g6-square. For instance, the manoeuvre ...Nf8-g6
is no longer possible and after a later ...g6, our kingside is weak.} 15. Rad1
Nf8 (15... g6)) (14... g6) 15. Rad1 b5 16. Bb1 Nb6 17. Bh4 Be7 (17... Nbd5 $5)
(17... Nfd5 $5) 18. Qd3 g6 $15 {A manoevering battle takes place. The
important thing is to stay flexible. Such games seldom end in draws and the
play can become sharp later on!} ({Let's suppose that we have played ...h6
earlier.} 18... h6 19. Bc2 g6 {No we get punished by} 20. Rxe6 $1 fxe6 21.
Qxg6+ Kh8 22. Bxf6+ $18 {Compare this to the comment after 14...h6.}) 19. Nf1
Bc6 20. N3d2 Qb7 21. Ne3 Nbd5 22. Nxd5 Bxd5 23. f3 a5) ({Let's suppose White
plays} 14. Bc2 {, when we already can afford to play} b5 $1 15. a4 (15. Rad1
Bc6 (15... Nb6) 16. Ne4 Bxe4 17. Bxe4 Nxe4 18. Qxe4 Nf6 19. Qe2 Qb7 20. Bh4 h6
{Even this is acceptable now; since White no longer has a light-squared bishop,
weakening of g6 is irrelevant.} {If White plays} 21. Bxf6 Bxf6 22. d5 {then} e5
$15 {in the spirit of the Najdorf Sicilian.}) 15... Bc6 16. axb5 (16. Bd3 bxa4)
16... axb5 $11) (14. a4 Qc8 {Covering a6 so that ...Bc6 becomes possible.})
14... b5 {Finally ...b5 is good. Since the rook has left the a-file, a2-a4 is
no longer to be feared.} 15. Nf1 (15. a4 $6 bxa4 16. Bc2 Bc6 {It's not easy
for White to recover the a-pawn since Black is about to attack b2.}) 15... Bc6
$5 {[%cal Yc7b7] What plan is connected to this move? We want to put the queen
on b7!} (15... Nb6) 16. a3 Qb7 17. Ne3 Nb6 $11 *

