1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 b6 5. c3 Bb7 6. Be2 Be7 7. h3 O-O 8. O-O a6
9. Nbd2 cxd4 10. exd4 d6 {We arrived at our setup via a different move order.}
11. Re1 Nbd7 {White's bishop is slightly misplaced on e2, but anyway in this
position it's not a matter of tempi.} 12. Bd3 Re8 13. Ne4 $6 {White loses his
patience and wants to do "something". But exchanges only help Black.} (13. c4
d5) 13... Bxe4 14. Bxe4 Nxe4 15. Rxe4 Nf6 16. Re2 b5 (16... Qd7) (16... Qc7 17.
a4 b5 18. axb5 axb5 19. Re1 Qb7 20. Qe2 d5 21. Ne5 b4) 17. a3 (17. a4 Qb6)
17... Qb6 18. Qc2 Qc6 (18... Qb7) (18... Rec8) (18... a5) 19. Rae1 a5 20. Qd2
Rac8 $15 {Black is already better.} 21. Bg5 Qc4 22. Bxf6 Bxf6 23. Re3 (23. d5
e5) 23... b4 $1 24. axb4 axb4 25. cxb4 Rb8 {Black regains the pawn and White
is left with two weaknesses on d4 and b2.} 26. Qc3 Qxb4 27. Qxb4 Rxb4 28. R1e2
Reb8 29. Rd3 Rxb2 (29... d5) 30. Rxb2 Rxb2 31. Nd2 d5 32. f4 ({After} 32. Nf3 {
we continue with the typical} g5 $1 {[%cal Yg8g7,Yg7g6,Yh7h5]} 33. g4 Kg7 34.
Kg2 Kg6 {Black can for instance prepare ...f6-e5.}) 32... g5 33. fxg5 Bxg5 34.
Nf3 Bf6 35. Ne5 Bxe5 36. dxe5 Re2 37. Rxd5 exd5 0-1

