1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 cxd4 5. exd4 b6 6. c3 Bb7 7. Nbd2 Be7 8. h3
O-O 9. Bd3 d6 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Re1 Qc7 12. a4 a6 13. Bh2 Rfe8 14. Qb3 Bf8 15.
Re2 {What to play now?} Bc6 {Carlsen plays the typical move, preparing ...Qb7.}
16. c4 ({After} 16. Rae1 {Black can directly play} b5 $1 17. axb5 axb5 18. Bxb5
Reb8 19. c4 Bxb5 20. cxb5 Qb7 $17 {Black regains the pawn with an advantage.})
16... Qb7 {Unpinning the d-pawn.} 17. Rae1 ({Black has to consider the gambit} 
17. d5 {but here it does not work} exd5 $17) 17... d5 {Against c4, we sooner
or later will need to play ...d5. Now White gets an isolated d-pawn.} 18. cxd5
Bxd5 19. Bc4 Rac8 20. Bxd5 Qxd5 21. Qxd5 Nxd5 {Black is clearly better in the
endgame - White has an isolated d-pawn and his pieces are misplaced.} 22. Ne4
Rc6 23. Ne5 Nxe5 24. dxe5 (24. Bxe5 f6 25. Bg3 Kf7 $17) 24... Rec8 {[%csl Gc6,
Gc8,Gd5,Re1,Re2,Rh2] White no longer has an isolated pawn, but now Black has
other advantages. Black can invade on the open c-file and his knight on d5
blocks the d-file.} 25. Bg3 Bb4 26. Rd1 Rc1 27. Rxc1 Rxc1+ 28. Kh2 h6 29. f3
Ra1 30. Rc2 Kh7 31. Bf2 Rxa4 $19 32. Nd6 Kg6 33. Rc4 f5 34. Rc6 Bd2 35. g3 b5
36. Nb7 Ra2 37. Rxe6+ Kh7 38. Bd4 Be3 39. Bxe3 Rxb2+ 40. Kg1 Nxe3 41. Rxa6 Rg2+
42. Kh1 Rxg3 43. f4 Rxh3+ 44. Kg1 Nd5 45. Nd6 Nxf4 46. Nxf5 Rh5 47. Nd4 Rxe5
48. Rb6 Ne2+ 49. Nxe2 Rxe2 50. Rxb5 Re6 0-1

