1. d4 Nf6 ({Against the lines with an early c3, we try to get a position like
this from the 4.e3-Slav (with Black!):} 1... d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 (
{or} 4... Bg4 5. Nc3 e6 6. Qb3 Qb6 7. Nh4 Nbd7 8. h3 Bh5 9. g4 Bg6 10. Nxg6
hxg6 11. Bg2) 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qb6 8. h3 Bh5 9. g4 Bg6 10. Nxg6 hxg6
11. Bg2) 2. Bf4 (2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 c5 4. c3 {This is another common move order!
Now we play} Nc6 $1 (4... cxd4 5. cxd4 Bb4+ {is another interesting way to
play.} ({The greedy} 5... Qb6 $6 6. Nc3 $1 Qxb2 7. Bd2 $16 {is too risky for
Black.})) 5. e3 {This is pretty much the only sensible move here, transposing
to 2.Nf3.} (5. Nbd2 $6 cxd4 6. cxd4 Qb6 7. Nc4 Bb4+ 8. Bd2 Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2 Qc7
10. e3 d5 $15 11. Nce5 $2 Ne4 12. Qc1 Qa5+ 13. Nd2 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Bd7 $17)) (2.
c3 e6 3. Bf4 c5 {is one more possible move order.}) 2... e6 3. e3 c5 4. c3 {
Now White is ready to take back on d4 with his c-pawn.} Nc6 $1 {A rare and
very good move!} ({Another alternative for us is} 4... b6 {We develop our
pieces and wait for Nbd2 to happen - we only exchange on d4, when Nc3 is no
longer possible.} 5. Nf3 Bb7 6. Nbd2 Be7 7. Bd3 cxd4 8. cxd4 {see the MODEL
GAME Kamsky-Gelfand.}) 5. Nf3 {transposing to 2.Nf3.} Nh5 $1 6. Bg5 $1 (6. Bg3
$6 Nxg3 7. hxg3 d5 8. Nbd2 (8. Bd3 h6 (8... g6 9. Nbd2 Qb6 10. Qb3 (10. Rb1 Bg7
(10... Be7)) 10... c4 11. Qxb6 axb6 12. Bc2 f5 13. a3 b5 14. Rd1 Bd6 15. g4 Ke7
16. gxf5 exf5) 9. g4) 8... g6 $5 {offers very good counterplay for Black! We
are not worried about weakening our dark squares, since White no longer has
his dark-squared bishop. I like this move even better than 8...Bd6. Study the
MODEL GAME, 0-1 (36) Shvedchikov,A (2353)-Moiseenko,A (2710) Moscow 2014.} ({
For} 8... Bd6 {see the MODEL GAME, 0-1 (32) Kukov,V (2392)-Parligras,M (2633)
Plovdiv 2013.})) (6. d5 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nf6 $1 {Black simply returns with the
knight and pushes d5 on the next move after which he is at least equal.} 8. Qb3
(8. Qd1 d5 9. Bb5 Bd6 $15 (9... Be7 $132)) 8... d5 9. Bb5 Bd6 $15 10. Bxc6+
bxc6 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. O-O O-O 13. Nbd2 Bf5 $15) 6... Qb6 $1 (6... Be7 $5 {
This is also simple and good, leading to a nice position for Black!} 7. Bxe7
Qxe7 8. Nbd2 cxd4 9. cxd4 (9. exd4 d6 $132) 9... O-O 10. a3 d6 $132) 7. Qb3 (7.
Nbd2 $5 h6 (7... d5 $6 8. dxc5 $3 Bxc5 9. b4 Be7 10. Bxe7 Nxe7 11. Be2 $14) (
7... Qxb2 $6 {This is risky.} 8. Rc1 Qb6 9. Nc4 Qc7 10. dxc5 $1 Bxc5 11. Nd4
$36) 8. Bh4 (8. Nc4 Qc7 9. Bh4 d5 10. Nce5 Bd6 $132) 8... d5 9. dxc5 Qxc5 (9...
Bxc5 10. b4 Bf8)) (7. Qc2 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 Nxg3 10. hxg3 Bg7 11. Nbd2 d5)
7... h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 Nxg3 10. hxg3 Bg7 $15 (10... d5 $4 11. Nxg5 $16) 11.
Nbd2 (11. Qxb6 axb6 12. Na3 d5 13. Nb5 Ke7 14. Be2 Bd7 $132) 11... d5 {Black
is slightly better due to his pair of bishops. For example} 12. Be2 (12. Qxb6
axb6 13. Bb5 Ke7 {Only Black can play for a win in this endgame.}) 12... Bd7
13. O-O cxd4 14. Qxb6 axb6 15. exd4 g4 16. Ne1 h5 17. Nd3 f6 18. Rfe1 Kf7 $15 *

