1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 (2... e6 {would be our move order.} 3. Nf3 c5 4. e3 cxd4)
3. e3 e6 4. c3 {If we now take on d4, White has the option to take back with
his c-pawn. This is the differenceto the move order 2.Nf3 e6 3.Bf4 c5 4.e3
cxd4, when White doesn't have the option to take with the c-pawn - 5.exd4. One
philosophy we can follow: if White plays an early c3, we wait with taking on
d4 until White has played Nbd2 - just like Gelfand did.} b6 5. Nf3 Bb7 6. Nbd2
Be7 7. Bd3 cxd4 8. cxd4 {Gelfand takes on d4 at a point when White's queen's
knight can no longer be developed to c3 (after cxd4).} Nc6 9. a3 Nh5 {Black
already has a good game.} 10. Bg3 O-O 11. Ne5 (11. Ng5 g6 12. Nxh7 Re8 13. Qg4
Kg7 $17) (11. O-O Nxg3 12. hxg3 d5 ({or} 12... Rc8 13. Qe2 d5) 13. Rc1 Qd6 $11
(13... Bd6 14. Qe2 f5)) 11... g6 12. Nxc6 dxc6 $5 (12... Bxc6 $15) 13. Be4 Qd7
(13... f5 $5 14. Bf3 f4 15. exf4 Qxd4 $36) 14. Nc4 c5 15. Ne5 Qc8 16. Bxb7 Qxb7
17. O-O Rfd8 18. Qf3 Qxf3 19. Nxf3 Nxg3 20. hxg3 Bf6 21. dxc5 bxc5 22. Rab1
Rab8 23. Rfc1 Rxb2 24. Rxb2 Bxb2 25. Rxc5 Rd1+ 26. Kh2 Rd5 27. Rxd5 exd5 28. a4
Kf8 29. Ne1 Ke7 30. Nd3 Bc3 31. g4 Kd6 32. Kg3 Kc6 33. Kf3 Kb6 34. Nf4 Ka5 35.
Nxd5 Bg7 36. Ne7 Kxa4 37. Nc6 a5 38. Ke4 Kb5 39. Nxa5 Kxa5 40. Kd5 g5 41. Kd6
Bc3 42. Ke7 f6 43. f4 Kb5 44. Kf7 Kc4 45. Kg7 Kd3 46. Kh6 gxf4 47. exf4 Ke4 48.
g3 Kf3 49. g5 f5 50. Kxh7 Kxg3 0-1

