1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 {This is the so-called Torre Attack, named after
Mexican player Carlos Torre Repetto. Like in the London System White simply
develops his bishop, followed in most cases by Nbd2, c3, Bd3 and short
castling. In contrast to Bf4, the f6-knight is pinned, so that e2-e4 becomes
an option.} c5 (3... d5 {This is maybe the best move objectively, but it's
difficult to play for a win with this.}) (3... h6 {is another interesting move.
} {Now} 4. Bxf6 (4. Bh4 c5 5. e3 {is another option. The inclusion of ...h6/
Bh4 has pros and cons for both sides.}) 4... Qxf6 5. e4 {leads to a line that
can also arise from the Trompowsky.}) 4. e3 {The main move - we are taking a
look at other options in the theorectical section.} cxd4 $1 5. exd4 Be7 {
We will base our repertoire on exactly the same setup as against the London
System! We build a Hedgehog position with the moves ...Be7, ...b6, ...Bb7, ...
d6, ...Nbd7, ...0-0, ...a6, ...Re8 - the order for moves can vary.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "TORRE ATTACK"]
[Black "THEORETICAL OVERVIEW"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A47"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "24"]
[EventDate "2024.06.13"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 c5 4. e3 (4. Nbd2 $6 {gives up the center. This has
no longer anything to do with the Torre Attack.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 d5 6. e3 Be7 $15
(6... e5)) (4. c3 {is played comparatively rarely.} {I suggest} cxd4 5. cxd4
Qb6 $5 $13) (4. d5 $5 {is an interesting alternative!} Qa5+ {is the best
continuation for Black - see MODEL GAME 0-1 (32) Serrano Salvador,E (2286)
-Zwardon,V (2482) Usti nad Labem 2022, and the following games (nr. 22-24).})
4... cxd4 $1 (4... b6 $2 {Be careful! Both in the London and in the Torre we
play ...c5 followed by ...cd4 on the very next move to avoid such
inconveniences! Famously, the great Anatoly Karpov committed this big mistake
two times in his career and was duly punished by Jussupow and Kamsky!} 5. d5 $1
$16 h6 (5... exd5 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Nxd5 Bb7 8. Bxf6 Bxf6 9. c3 O-O 10. Bc4 $16 {
see MODEL GAME nr. 4, 1-0 (37) Jussupow,A (2610)-Karpov,A (2755) London 1989
Candidates.}) 6. Bxf6 Qxf6 7. Nc3 Qd8 8. Bc4 (8. Ne5 $1 $18) 8... Be7 9. O-O
O-O 10. e4 $16 {see MODEL GAME nr. 5, 1-0 (47) Kamsky,G (2723)-Karpov,A (2651)
Moscow 2008.}) 5. exd4 (5. Nxd4 $4 {loses the bishop:} Qa5+ $19) 5... Be7 {
We use exactly the same setup as against the London System! We build a
Hedgehog position with the moves ...Be7, ...b6, ...Bb7, ...d6, ...Nbd7, ...0-0,
...a6, ...Re8 - the order for moves can vary.} ({We can also start with} 5...
b6 {but then there is maybe} 6. d5 {, although the computer thinks that the
complications are favourable for Black.}) 6. Bd3 b6 7. Nbd2 Bb7 (7... Ba6 $5 {
can be an interesting alternative - check out the MODEL GAME Nr. 16 0-1 (58)
Buckley,G (2342)-Arkell,K (2499) London 2015.}) 8. c3 d6 {I like to postpone
castling and to connect our knights with ...Nbd7 as fast as possible.} 9. O-O (
9. Bxf6 $5 Bxf6 10. Qe2 {The Miladinovic-Attack! We have to know how to react
against this - study the games 17-21 in the database.}) 9... Nbd7 10. Re1 O-O
11. Qe2 (11. c4 {is well met with} d5) (11. a4 {is almost always met with} a6 {
to be able to play ...b5 in reply to a5.}) 11... Re8 12. a4 a6 {Black has
completed his basic setup. Study the MODEL GAMES Nr. 6-15 to get an
understanding of the typical plans and motifs of these Hedgehog positions! We
have seen examples with similar play in our lecture on the London System.} *

