{In this game, the high-level GM with the black pieces commits a serious
mistake by playing ...d6-d5? After that, White was better although Black still
managed to win the game!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 c5 4. e3 cxd4 5. exd4 b6
6. Bd3 Bb7 7. Nbd2 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 d6 10. Bxf6 {A playable move.} Bxf6
11. Be4 d5 $2 {I don't like this choice at all. Black wants to keep the pair
of bishops, but with this bad b7-bishop this is the wrong strategy.} (11... Qc7
$1 {looks like the most logical move.} 12. c3 (12. d5 $2 exd5 ({Even after} 
12... e5 $15 {Black is better.}) 13. Bd3 Bxb2 $19) 12... Nd7 $11) 12. Bd3 Nc6
13. c3 $14 g6 14. Qe2 Bg7 15. Ne5 $6 (15. h4 $1 {White has good chances on the
kingside.}) 15... Ne7 ({Black had a chance to get counterplay.} 15... Nxe5 $1
16. dxe5 d4 $1 17. c4 {Statically White's position is very good, but Black can
free his game with the help of tactics.} Qg5 $1 18. g3 Bxe5 $1 $132) 16. a4 $5
(16. h4 $1 $16) 16... Nc8 17. a5 Nd6 18. h3 {White loses the thread of the
game.} (18. a6 $14) 18... Qc7 19. h4 Rae8 $13 {Now Black has consolidated his
position and went on to outplay his opponent.} 20. axb6 axb6 21. Nef3 f6 22. c4
Bh6 23. b3 Bf4 24. Ra2 f5 25. Rc2 Qg7 26. c5 bxc5 27. dxc5 Ne4 28. c6 Bc8 29.
b4 Bc7 30. Nb3 e5 31. Ba6 Be6 32. Ng5 Nxg5 33. hxg5 e4 34. Nc5 Qe5 35. g3 f4
36. Nd7 Bxd7 37. cxd7 Rd8 38. Qg4 fxg3 39. Qxg3 Qxg3+ 40. fxg3 Rxd7 41. Bb5 Re7
42. Bc6 Rf5 43. Rd1 Bb6+ 44. Kg2 d4 45. Re2 e3 46. b5 Rxg5 47. Rd3 Kg7 48. Ra3
Bc7 49. Rd3 Rxg3+ 50. Kh1 Bb6 51. Kh2 Rg4 52. Kh3 h5 53. Re1 Kh6 54. Bf3 Rf4
55. Kg2 Ref7 56. Rf1 R7f5 57. Be2 Rf2+ 0-1

