{In this nice game, Black used another instructive idea (which is also quite
good against the London system): he put his bishop on a6 instead of b7!
WHENEVER THE MOVE ORDER ALLOWS IT, YOU SHOULD ALSO CONSIDER THIS IDEA!} 1. d4
Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 c5 4. e3 cxd4 5. exd4 Be7 6. Nbd2 O-O ({or} 6... b6 7. Bd3
{and again the idea} Ba6 {is possible.} {What do we play after} 8. c4 {? We
already know the answer:} O-O 9. O-O d5 $1 $11 {with equal chances.}) 7. Bd3 b6
8. O-O Ba6 $1 {This is not our repertoire, but nevertheless a playable
alternative. On the one hand it is useful to exchange the light-squared
bishops, on the other, the knight will be temporarily misplaced on a6.} (8...
Bb7 $1) 9. Bxa6 (9. c4 $6 d5 10. Re1 dxc4 11. Nxc4 Nc6 $132) 9... Nxa6 10. c3
Nc7 $11 11. a4 a6 12. Ne5 (12. Bxf6 {In my opinion White should capture this
knight.}) 12... h6 13. Bh4 Nfd5 14. Bg3 Qc8 15. Re1 Nf6 16. Qf3 b5 17. Bh4 Ncd5
18. h3 d6 19. Nd3 Re8 20. Ra2 Nb6 {Forcing White to clarify the situation.} 21.
axb5 axb5 22. Rea1 Rxa2 23. Rxa2 Nc4 24. Nf1 d5 25. Bxf6 Bxf6 {Up to now, the
position was about equal, but White commits a serious strategic error with his
next move.} 26. b3 $2 Nd6 $17 27. Nb4 Ne4 28. Rc2 Qd7 29. Qd3 Ra8 30. f3 Nd6
31. Ra2 Rc8 32. Ne3 Qc7 33. Nd1 Qb7 34. Qb1 Nf5 35. Qa1 Qc7 36. Ra8 Rxa8 37.
Qxa8+ Kh7 38. Qa2 Qf4 39. Qc2 Kg8 40. Nd3 Qc7 41. Qf2 Qa7 42. Qe1 Qa2 43. b4
Qc2 44. N3f2 Bh4 45. g4 Bxf2+ 46. Nxf2 Nh4 47. Qe3 Qd2 48. Qxd2 Nxf3+ 49. Kf1
Nxd2+ 50. Ke2 Nc4 51. Nd3 f6 52. Nc5 Kf7 53. Na6 Nd6 54. Nb8 Ke7 55. Nc6+ Kd7
56. Nb8+ Kc8 57. Nc6 Kc7 58. Ne7 Ne4 0-1

