1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 {This is not in fact the Torre, but the Trompowsky opening,
which may sometimes transpose to the Torre (if both players want this)!} e6 (
2... d5 $1 {this is the best move!}) 3. e3 c5 4. c3 cxd4 5. exd4 (5. cxd4 $4
Qa5+ $19) 5... Be7 6. Nf3 d6 {[%cal Yb8d7]} 7. Bxf6 $5 {SUPER SOS! This is a
very very interesting system for White! .He takes on f6 right before Black can
connect his knights with ...Nbd7. Now, Black has to take on f6 with his bishop,
and then play Nd7, when White's idea is simple: Play Bd3-Bxf6-Qe2-c3-0-0-0 and
h4-g4 etc. with very easy and dangerous play! BLACK SHOULD REACT BY POSTPONING
...0-0, and play as many useful moves as he can and hope that White runs out
of constructive ideas!} Bxf6 8. Nbd2 Be7 $1 (8... O-O $6 {SOS! This is what
most players would play as Black. This however offers White a very easy game
and nice attacking chances!} 9. Bd3 Nc6 10. Qe2 $1 Bd7 11. O-O-O Rc8 12. Kb1 a6
13. h4 $36 {and ideas with Bxh7+ are always in the air!}) 9. Bd3 Nd7 10. Qe2 a6
$1 {I am ready to go ...b5 in one move, if he castles long!} 11. h4 (11. O-O
Nf6 $1 12. Rfe1 b6 13. Rad1 Bb7 $132 14. h3 O-O $1 {Now I can castle short
because he did the same! Black gets a very nice version of the Hedgehog where
he is already slightly better in a practical sense!}) 11... b5 (11... Nf6 $5 {
This might have been a bit more ...scientific!}) 12. O-O-O (12. a4 bxa4 13.
Rxa4 Nb6 14. Ra2 a5 15. Bb5+ Bd7 $132 {Yes, the a-pawn is weak, but now h4
makes no sense at all.}) 12... Qc7 13. Kb1 Bb7 {We have an unclear position
with chances for both sides. Since we didn't offer White a target by playing ..
.0-0?!, White's attack is not going anywhere.} 14. Ng5 Nf6 $132 15. Rhe1 {
After some serious calculation I played} h6 $1 $15 {since I saw that
sacrifices don't work.} 16. Nh3 (16. Nxf7 Kxf7 17. Qxe6+ Kf8 $15 18. Bg6 Bd5
$17) (16. Nge4 Nd5 17. g3 O-O $5 {Now it's alright if I castle.} (17... Rc8 $5
$132)) 16... Bxg2 $1 {I wanted to play for a win and took on g2. White will
get some compensation, but I was willing to defend this position and keep my
extra pawn.} 17. Nf4 Bb7 18. Rg1 Rg8 19. Nh5 Nxh5 20. Qxh5 Bf6 21. Rc1 Ke7 22.
Rce1 Kf8 23. Qg4 Rb8 24. f4 b4 $1 $17 {After consolidating my position I go
for active counterplay.} 25. c4 Bxd4 26. Rgf1 g6 27. Qg3 h5 28. Be4 Bxe4+ 29.
Nxe4 Qxc4 30. Nxd6 Qd5 31. Ne4 b3 32. a3 Rc8 33. Rf3 Kg7 34. f5 exf5 35. Nd6
Rc2 36. Rxb3 Rg2 37. Qh3 Rd8 38. Ne8+ Rxe8 39. Rxe8 Rg1+ 40. Ka2 Bxb2 $1 41.
Qf3 Qc4 0-1

