1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {With this move order, White wants to later
transpose to the Catalan, without giving Black the options of playing ...dxc4 
(as after 3.c4 d5 4.g3 dxc4) and ...Bb4+ (after 3.c4 Bb4+ or 3...d5 4.g3 Bb4+).
Black can give the game an independent direction with either 3...c5 or 3...b5,
the latter being our repertoire.} b5 {With 3...b5 we control c4 and quickly
solve the problem of neutralising White's Catalan bishop by developing our
bishop to b7. We have a case where a more rarely played continuation is quite
good!} ({The main move is} 3... d5 {which can lead to a Catalan after} 4. Bg2
Be7 5. c4) (3... c5 {can lead to a line from the English Opening and is also
fine in a theoretical sense. For example} 4. c4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 d5 6. Bg2 e5 7.
Nf3 d4 8. O-O Nc6 9. e3 Be7 {with good chances for equality.}) 4. Bg2 Bb7 5.
O-O c5 {Black gets a satisfactory game with good chances to take over the
initiative, should White play too passively.} ({Another option is} 5... d5 {
Now White can no longer transpose to the Catalan, since Black firmly controls
c4.}) *

