1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {With this move order, White wants to transpose to
the Catalan without allowing lines with an early ...dxc4 and ...Bb4+.} b5 {
This is the Polish variation - from a practical perspective it's the best
option in this position. Black doesn't need to know much theory. Plans and
general ideas matter a lot more!} (3... d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. c4 {leads to the
Catalan.}) 4. Bg2 (4. Qd3 {A playable but pretty harmless variation!} a6 $1 (
4... Ba6 $5 {is also totally playable - again no theory is needed; we just
logical moves.} 5. Bg2 d5 6. O-O c5 $132) 5. e4 Bb7 6. Nbd2 {White has
occupied the center, but his pieces are somewhat misplaced.} (6. e5 Nd5 {
see MODEL GAME ½-½ (53) Dardha,D (2485)-Niemann,H (2484) Bassano del Grappa
2021.}) 6... c5 7. c3 d5 (7... cxd4 $5 8. cxd4 Nc6 9. a3 Na5 $1 $132) 8. e5
Nfd7 $132 {Black has good counterplay on the queenside; for example} (8... Ne4)
9. Bg2 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 Nc6 12. Nf1 b4 13. h4 a5 $11) (4. Nc3 $5 b4 5.
Na4 Bb7 6. Bg2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. c4 bxc3 9. Nxc3 c5 $132) (4. e3 a6 {This is
the right reaction.} ({After} 4... b4 $6 5. a3 $1 $14 {Black ends up with an
isolated a-pawn.}) 5. a4 b4 {see MODEL GAME 0-1 (38) Fica Cruz,J (1949)
-Tsolakidou,S (2379) Tornelo INT 2021.}) (4. Bg5 Be7) 4... Bb7 (4... d5 $5 {
is the other possibility.}) 5. O-O (5. Bg5 c5 6. Bxf6 (6. c3 Be7 $11) 6... Qxf6
7. c3 Qd8 8. O-O Be7 $11) 5... c5 {This is the move I prefer and the most
logical one.} 6. c3 {Now, White wants to play 7.a4, and we want to be ready to
meet this with 7...b4! 8.cb4 Nxb4! So we need to play 6...Na6! or 6...cxd4!} (
6. a4 b4 7. c3 {Now we can either take on c3 or play ...Na6.} (7. Nbd2 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 (8. Nb3 Be7 {see MODEL GAME 0-1 (44) Martic,Z (2364)-Kovacevic,V (2471)
Sibenik 2011.}) 8... Bxg2 9. Kxg2 Be7 (9... Nc6 $4 {A horrible move resulting
in a bad position!} 10. Nxc6 dxc6 11. e4 $16 (11. Nc4 $4 Qd5+ 12. Qxd5 cxd5 $15
) 11... Be7 12. Qe2 O-O 13. Nc4 $16) 10. b3 O-O 11. Bb2 d5 $15 {Black has the
advantage - he controls the center and White has a backward c-pawn.} (11... Qb6
{Is also good, for example} 12. Nc4 Qb7+ 13. Kg1 Nc6 14. Nxc6 Qxc6 15. Qd3 d5
16. Ne5 Qb7 $17) 12. c4 bxc3 13. Bxc3 Qb6 14. a5 Qb7 15. Kg1 Na6 $17) (7. c4
cxd4 $1 {Here we must play ...cxd4 because White was threatening d4-d5!.} (7...
bxc3 {see 7.c3.}) (7... Be7 8. d5 $1 exd5 9. Nh4 $36) 8. Nxd4 Bxg2 9. Kxg2 Na6
10. b3 Be7 11. Bb2 Nc5 12. Nd2 O-O $15 {We plan to play ...d6-g6!! and ...e5!}
13. Qc2 Qb6 14. Rad1 Qb7+ 15. N4f3 Rac8 16. Qb1 d6 $15) 7... Na6 (7... bxc3 {
is possible, although we help White's development.} 8. Nxc3 $1 ({Black is fine
after} 8. bxc3 Be7 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Re1 Na6 $3 11. e4 cxd4 12. cxd4 d5 $1 (12...
Nb4) 13. e5 Nd7 14. Rb1 Nb4 15. Ba3 a5 $15) 8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Bxg2 10. Kxg2 Qb6
11. e4 Nc6 12. Be3 Qb7 13. Nxc6 Qxc6 14. f3 Be7 15. Rc1 $16) 8. c4 {Now White
has a threat: to play d4-d5!} cxd4 (8... Be7 $2 9. d5 $1 exd5 10. Nh4 $36) 9.
Nxd4 Bxg2 10. Kxg2 Be7 (10... Qb6 11. e3 Qb7+ 12. Qf3) 11. b3 O-O 12. Bb2 Nc5
13. Nd2 Qb6 (13... a6 {I also like this simple move, controlling b5.}) 14. e3
a6 (14... Qb7+ $5 15. Qf3 Nfe4 $1 {Black should not exchange queens - it is
easier to exploit the weaknesses in White's position with queens on the board.}
) (14... Nd3 {does not offer too much since we don't want to exchange the
strong c5-knight against White's bishop.}) 15. Rb1 d6 {Black has a great
position.} 16. Qf3 Rac8 $17 {Later, we might play ...g6 (to control f5) and ...
e5.}) (6. dxc5 $6 Bxc5 7. Bg5 (7. a4 b4 8. Bf4 d5) (7. Nbd2 O-O 8. a4 (8. Re1
$4 Bxf2+ $1 9. Kxf2 Ng4+ 10. Kg1 Ne3 $19) (8. c4 bxc4 (8... a6) 9. Nxc4 d5 10.
Nce5 Nbd7 $11) (8. b3 d5 9. Bb2 Nbd7 10. c4 dxc4 11. bxc4 b4 $15) 8... b4 9.
Nb3 Be7 $15 {Black is already better because White has absolutely no pawn
play! See MODEL GAME 0-1 (53) Yhk24 (2667)-Vastazos (2716).}) 7... O-O (7... h6
{I would play this move later - the queen feels a little clumsy on f6.} 8. Bxf6
Qxf6 9. c3 O-O 10. Qd3) (7... Be7) 8. Nbd2 Be7 9. c3 Nc6 10. e4 h6 (10... d6)
11. Bxf6 Bxf6 {Black has an excellent Sicilian type of position.}) (6. Bg5 $5
cxd4 $1 (6... Be7 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Qd3 a6 $13) (6... Na6 $4 7. e4 $3 Bxe4 8. Nc3
Bc6 9. d5 $18 exd5 10. Re1+ Be7 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Nh4 $18 (12. Nxd5 $18)) 7.
Nxd4 Bxg2 8. Kxg2 a6 9. c3 Be7 10. Nd2 (10. a4 b4) 10... O-O $11) (6. b3 {
see MODEL GAME 0-1 (62) Beikert,G (2465)-Papaioannou,I (2605) Aix les Bains
2011.}) 6... Na6 $1 {Now, we study some sample lines:} (6... Be7 {is slightly
inaccurate. Let me show you how White can get an advantage:} 7. a4 b4 8. cxb4
cxb4 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Nb3 a5 11. Bg5 {White wants to exchange on f6 and then to
exchange the light-squared bishops, leaving him with a good knight against
Black's dark-squared bishop. This was a favourite strategy of the great
endgame specialist Ulf Andersson!} d6 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Ne1 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Qb6
15. e3 Nd7 16. Nd3 Qb7+ 17. Qf3 {White is very happy to exchange the queens.}
Qxf3+ 18. Kxf3 $14 {Black is suffering in the endgame - he has a permanent
weakness on a5.}) (6... cxd4 $1 {This is maybe the best objectively - reaching
a symmetrical pawn structure with an equal game!} 7. cxd4 (7. Nxd4 Bxg2 8. Kxg2
a6 (8... Qb6) 9. a4 b4 $132) 7... h6 $1 (7... Be7 8. Bg5 a6 $11) 8. a4 bxa4 9.
Rxa4 Be7 $11) 7. a4 (7. dxc5 $6 Nxc5 $15 8. Nd4 {Should we take on g2 and
protect b5 or protect b5 right away?} Bxg2 {First taking on g2 is better,
since White's king will be exposed on g2.} 9. Kxg2 {For example} a6 {Black is
already slightly better. White doesn't have any pawn play!} 10. Bg5 Be7 11. Nd2
O-O {Black can prepare ...d5-e5 with play in the center or ...a5-b4 with a
minority attack.} 12. N2f3 Qc7 13. Nb3 Na4 14. Qc2 h6 (14... d5) 15. Bxf6 Bxf6
16. e4 d6 $15) (7. Bg5 Be7 8. Nbd2 (8. dxc5 Nxc5 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Qc2 (10. Nb3
Na4 $1 $15) 10... Qc7 (10... d5) 11. Bxf6 (11. Rfd1 Rac8 $15) 11... Bxf6 12. e4
d5 $15 (12... d6 $15)) (8. e3 O-O 9. Qe2 Qb6 10. Nbd2 h6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 $11)
8... O-O 9. Bxf6 {Giving up the bishop in order to play e2-e4.} (9. a4 b4 10.
cxb4 Nxb4 $15 11. Rc1 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 h6 (13... a5 $2 {We should
not give up control over the b5-square and rather keep the option to play ...
a6.} 14. Nb5) 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. N2f3 Qb6 16. e3 a6 17. Qe2 Qb7 $15 {Black has
a clear advantage: White's b2-pawn is weak and we can play in the center.}) (9.
Re1 h6 10. Bxf6 (10. Bf4 Nd5) 10... Bxf6 11. e4 cxd4 (11... d5 12. e5 Be7) 12.
cxd4 Qb6 13. e5 Be7) 9... Bxf6 10. e4 {This e4-advance is hardly ever
dangerous. We can play ...d5, ...d6, or ignore it!} d5 $1 (10... d6 $5 11. Qe2
cxd4 12. cxd4 Qb6 13. e5 dxe5 14. dxe5 Be7 $15) (10... Qb6 $5 11. e5 Be7 12.
Re1 cxd4 13. Nxd4 (13. cxd4 Nb4) 13... Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Nc5 (14... Qb7+ {We
should not give this check, since we don't want to exchange queens after} 15.
Qf3) 15. Qe2 a6 (15... d6) 16. Rad1 d6 17. exd6 Bxd6 $15) 11. e5 (11. exd5 Bxd5
) 11... Be7 12. h4 b4 $15 {We are a lot faster with our play on the queenside.}
) (7. Na3 Nc7 $132) 7... b4 8. cxb4 Nxb4 9. Nc3 (9. Bf4 d5 (9... Be7 10. Nc3
O-O 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Bd6 Bxd6 13. Qxd6 a5 14. Rad1 Bc6 15. Ne5 Bxg2 16. Kxg2
Ra7 17. e3 Qa8+)) 9... cxd4 $5 (9... d5 $5) (9... Be7 $5 10. Re1 d5 (10... cxd4
11. Nxd4 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 d5 (12... a5 $2 13. Ndb5) (12... O-O 13. e4 d6 (13...
Qb6 14. Be3 Qb7 15. f3 d5 (15... a6) 16. e5 Nd7) 14. Be3 Qd7 15. Rc1 Qb7 16. f3
a6 17. Qd2 Rfc8)) 11. Bf4 O-O 12. e3 Rc8 13. Ne5 Ba6 14. Qd2 Nd7 15. Nxd7 Qxd7
16. Rac1 Bd6 17. Bxd6 Qxd6 18. h3 cxd4 19. exd4 Qb6 (19... Nd3)) 10. Nxd4 Bxg2
11. Kxg2 Be7 12. e4 d6 (12... O-O 13. e5 Nfd5 14. Ne4 (14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. b3 (
15. Re1) 15... Rc8 16. Bb2 d6 17. exd6 Qxd6) 14... d6 15. exd6 Bxd6 16. Nxd6
Qxd6) 13. Be3 a6 14. Qd2 O-O 15. Rfd1 Qd7 16. f3 Qb7 17. Rac1 d5 18. e5 Nd7 19.
f4 Nc5 *

