1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 b5 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. O-O c5 6. a4 b4 7. Nbd2 cxd4 8. Nb3
Be7 9. a5 O-O (9... Na6 {Immediately stopping any tricks connected to a5-a6.})
10. Nbxd4 a6 (10... Na6 $1 {According to my analysis, this move is best. Black
is better due to the backward c2-pawn and the central pawn majority. White has
no pawn play, whereas Black can go forward with his central pawns.} 11. Bg5 Nc5
(11... h6 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 $17) 12. Re1 Rc8 $17) 11. Re1 Qc8 ({I don't like} 11...
Nc6 12. Ne5) (11... d5) 12. Bg5 h6 (12... Nc6 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. Qd2 Qb7 $15 (
14... Ne4)) 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Qd2 (14. e4 Nc6 15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. e5 Be7 {
This strongly resembles a Taimanov Sicilian in a very good version for Black.
For example} 17. Nd4 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Qc5 19. Nb3 Qc6+ 20. Kg1 d6 21. exd6 Bxd6
$17) 14... Nc6 15. c3 (15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. Qxb4 Rb8 $17 {Black recovers the pawn
with a clear advantage.}) 15... bxc3 16. bxc3 Qc7 $17 17. Qb2 Nxa5 18. Rxa5
Bxf3 (18... Qxa5 19. Qxb7 Qxc3 $19 {was also very good.}) 19. Rea1 Bxg2 20.
Kxg2 Rfb8 21. Qd2 Rb6 {Black has won a pawn and kept his positional advantage.}
22. Qd3 Qb7+ 23. f3 d5 24. h4 h5 25. R1a2 g6 26. f4 Kg7 27. Kh2 Qc8 28. R2a4
Ra7 29. Kg2 Rc7 30. Rxa6 Rxc3 31. Rxb6 Rxd3 32. exd3 Bxd4 33. Rxd4 Qc2+ 34. Kf3
Qc1 35. Kf2 Qc5 36. Rbb4 f6 37. Kg2 Kh6 38. Ra4 e5 39. Rdb4 Qc2+ 40. Kh3 Qxd3
41. Ra8 Qf1+ 42. Kh2 Qf2+ 43. Kh3 Qe1 44. Rb2 exf4 0-1

