1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 b5 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. O-O c5 6. c3 Na6 7. a4 b4 8. Nbd2
Be7 9. Re1 (9. dxc5 $6 bxc3 $1 10. bxc3 Nxc5 {Black is at least slightly
better.}) 9... d5 {This move is fine, but I am not a very big fan of it.} (9...
O-O $1 10. e4 {Now Black can get a strategic advantage:} bxc3 ({But not} 10...
cxd4 $2 11. cxd4 {and we are left with a pawn on b4, taking away this square
from the a6-knight.}) 11. bxc3 cxd4 12. cxd4 (12. Nxd4 {White is threatening
e4-e5 (since our b7-bishop is not protected).} Nc5 {Protecting the bishop with
a natural move.} {After} 13. e5 Nd5 {we will later challenge the e5-pawn with .
..d6, or maybe even ...f6.}) 12... Nb4 13. Rb1 a5 $1 14. h3 (14. e5 Nfd5 15.
Ne4 Rc8) 14... d5 15. e5 Nd7 $3 $17) 10. Ne5 O-O 11. Ndf3 Rc8 12. Be3 Ne4 13.
cxb4 Nxb4 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Bxc5 Nxc5 {Black has achieved a clear advantage:
White's b-pawn is weak, the b4-square is weak and we have an extra central
pawn.} 16. a5 Ba6 $1 17. Bf1 Qd6 18. Rc1 Qc7 19. Qd4 Qxa5 20. Ra1 Qb6 21. Rec1
{Now Black makes good use of his central pawn majority:} f6 22. Ng4 e5 23. Qd1
d4 $19 {Black already has a strategically winning position.} 24. h4 h5 25. Ngh2
Rc7 26. Ra3 Bc8 27. Nd2 Be6 28. Nc4 Qb8 29. Ra5 Rfc8 30. Na3 Nb3 31. Rxc7 Qxc7
32. Rb5 a5 33. Qb1 Rb8 34. Rxb8+ Qxb8 35. Bg2 Qc8 36. Nf1 f5 37. Bf3 g6 38. e4
dxe3 39. fxe3 Qc1 40. Bd1 Qxb1 41. Nxb1 Nd3 42. e4 fxe4 43. Ne3 Nxb2 44. Bc2
Nc5 45. Na3 Nbd3 46. Kf1 Kg7 47. Ke2 Kf6 48. Kd2 Nb4 49. Bd1 Nc6 50. Nec4 Bxc4
51. Nxc4 a4 52. Ke3 Ne7 53. g4 hxg4 54. Bxg4 Nf5+ 55. Kd2 Nxh4 56. Kc3 Ng2 57.
Kb4 Nd3+ 58. Kxa4 0-1

