{ONE OF THE BEST GAMES THAT I HAVE EVER PLAYED!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 b5
4. Bg2 Bb7 5. O-O c5 6. b3 Be7 (6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 Bxg2 8. Kxg2 Qb6 9. Bb2 Nc6)
7. Bb2 O-O 8. c4 bxc4 9. dxc5 Na6 $5 {A nice little move - I want to capture
on c5 with the knight.} 10. bxc4 Nxc5 11. Nbd2 Rc8 $15 {Black is slightly
better. White has a weak c-pawn, but he can put the d7-pawn under pressure.}
12. Qc2 Nfe4 13. Rfd1 f5 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Qd2 Bxf3 $3 {An excellent
positional decision! I anticipated that White wanted to move his knight to e1
or e5 to challenge my strong knight on c5 (with for example Nd3) - then the
weakness of the d7-pawn would have been felt. I gave up my strong bishop
because I saw that I could exchange the dark-squared bishops on the very next
move. By this operation the c5-knight becomes unassailable! My opponent was
shocked when I played 15...Bxf3!!.} (15... Bf6 16. Ne1 (16. Ne5) 16... Bxg2 17.
Kxg2 Bxb2 18. Qxb2 Qe7 19. Nd3 $132) 16. Bxf3 Bf6 $15 {WHITE IS LEFT WITH A
BAD LIGHT-SQUARED BISHOP AGAINST A STRONG KNIGHT ON c5!} 17. Rab1 Bxb2 18. Rxb2
Qc7 19. Qd4 (19. Kg2 {allows} Qe5 $1 20. Qd4 Qxd4 21. Rxd4 Kf7 $15) 19... Kh8
20. Qe3 h6 21. Rb5 a6 22. Rb2 Rce8 $1 (22... Rb8 23. Rdb1 Rxb2 24. Rxb2) 23.
Rdb1 f4 {By driving away his queen, I will manage to put my queen on the
beautiful e5-square.} 24. Qa3 fxg3 (24... Qe5 25. g4) 25. hxg3 Qe5 26. Qa5 h5
27. Kg2 Kg8 (27... h4 28. Rh1 $1 Qxb2 $2 29. Rxh4+ Kg8 30. Qxc5 $16 {[%csl Rg8]
}) 28. Qd2 h4 29. Qc2 hxg3 30. fxg3 Kf7 $3 (30... Rf5 31. g4 Rg5 32. Rh1) 31.
Qd2 Ke7 {The king is safe on e7, protected by the centralised queen and
powerful knight on c5. In the further course of the game, I managed to create
threats against the white king, forcing him to exchange queens, and exploited
the weaknesses in White's position in the endgame.} 32. Rb6 Rh8 33. Rd1 Rh6 34.
Qf4 Qxf4 35. gxf4 Rf8 36. Rd4 Rh4 37. Kg3 Rfh8 38. Rd1 R4h6 39. Kf2 Rh4 40. Ke3
Rf8 41. Rd4 Rf5 42. Rb8 g5 43. Rg8 Rhxf4 44. Rxf4 Rxf4 45. Rxg5 Rxc4 46. Rg1 d5
47. Rb1 Kd6 48. Kd2 Rd4+ 49. Kc2 Ra4 50. Kb2 Rb4+ 51. Kc2 Rc4+ 52. Kd2 Ra4 53.
Rb2 Ra3 54. e3 Ke5 55. Bg4 Ne4+ 56. Ke2 Rxa2 57. Rxa2 Nc3+ 58. Kd2 Nxa2 59. Be2
a5 60. Bb5 Kd6 61. Be8 e5 62. Kc2 e4 (62... Kc5 63. Kb3 Nb4 64. Kc3 d4+ 65.
exd4+ exd4+ 66. Kd2 Kc4 67. Bf7+ Nd5 68. Be8 Nc3 69. Bf7+ Kc5 70. Kd3 a4 71.
Bg8 a3 72. Kc2 a2 73. Kb2 d3 74. Bf7 d2 75. Bh5 Kd4 76. Ka1 Ke3 77. Bf7 Kf2 78.
Bb3 Ke1 79. Bc2 d1=Q+ 80. Bxd1) 63. Kb3 (63. Bf7 Kc5 64. Be6 Nb4+ 65. Kd2 Nc6
66. Bd7 Ne5 67. Be8 Nc4+ 68. Ke2 Kb4 69. Bc6 Nb6 70. Kd1 a4 71. Kc1 (71. Kc2
Nc4) 71... Kc3 72. Bb5 a3 73. Kb1 Kd2) 63... Nb4 64. Ka4 Nc2 0-1

